# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biochemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:biochemistry/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids can be classified according to the locations of the core structural functional groups (alpha- (α-), beta- (β-), gamma- (γ-) amino acids, etc.); other categories relate to polarity, ionization, and side-chain group type (aliphatic, acyclic, aromatic, polar, etc.).
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In the form of proteins, amino-acid *residues* form the second-largest component (water being the largest) of human muscles and other tissues.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Beyond their role as residues in proteins, amino acids participate in a number of processes such as neurotransmitter transport and biosynthesis.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] It is thought that they played a key role in enabling life on Earth and its emergence.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids are formally named by the IUPAC-IUBMB Joint Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature in terms of the fictitious "neutral" structure shown in the illustration.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, the systematic name of alanine is 2-aminopropanoic acid, based on the formula CH3−CH(NH2)−COOH.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The first few amino acids were discovered in the early 1800s.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In 1806, French chemists Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin and Pierre Jean Robiquet isolated a compound from asparagus that was subsequently named asparagine, the first amino acid to be discovered.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Cystine was discovered in 1810, although its monomer, cysteine, remained undiscovered until 1884.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Glycine and leucine were discovered in 1820.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The last of the 20 common amino acids to be discovered was threonine in 1935 by William Cumming Rose, who also determined the essential amino acids and established the minimum daily requirements of all amino acids for optimal growth.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The unity of the chemical category was recognized by Wurtz in 1865, but he gave no particular name to it.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The first use of the term "amino acid" in the English language dates from 1898, while the German term, *Aminosäure*, was used earlier.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Proteins were found to yield amino acids after enzymatic digestion or acid hydrolysis.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In 1902, Emil Fischer and Franz Hofmeister independently proposed that proteins are formed from many amino acids, whereby bonds are formed between the amino group of one amino acid with the carboxyl group of another, resulting in a linear structure that Fischer termed "peptide".
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] 2-, alpha-, or α-amino acids have the generic formula H2NCHRCOOH in most cases, where R is an organic substituent known as a "side chain".
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Of the many hundreds of described amino acids, 22 are proteinogenic ("protein-building").
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] It is these 22 compounds that combine to give a vast array of peptides and proteins assembled by ribosomes.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids may arise through nonribosomal peptide synthesis.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Modified amino acids, by contrast, typically result from post-translational modification.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CO−2, such as β-alanine, a component of carnosine and a few other peptides, are β-amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Ones with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CXY−CO−2 are γ-amino acids, and so on, where X and Y are two substituents (one of which is normally H).
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The carbon atom next to the carboxyl group is called the α–carbon.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In proteinogenic amino acids, it bears the amine and the R group or side chain specific to each amino acid, as well as a hydrogen atom.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] With the exception of glycine, for which the side chain is also a hydrogen atom, the α–carbon is stereogenic.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] All chiral proteinogenic amino acids have the L configuration.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] They are "left-handed" enantiomers, which refers to the stereoisomers of the alpha carbon.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] A few D-amino acids ("right-handed") have been found in nature, e.g., in bacterial envelopes, as a neuromodulator (D-serine), and in some antibiotics.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Rarely, D-amino acid residues are found in proteins, and are converted from the L-amino acid as a post-translational modification.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Five amino acids possess a charge at neutral pH.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Often these side chains appear at the surfaces on proteins to enable their solubility in water, and side chains with opposite charges form important electrostatic contacts called salt bridges that maintain structures within a single protein or between interfacing proteins.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Many proteins bind metal into their structures specifically, and these interactions are commonly mediated by charged side chains such as aspartate, glutamate and histidine.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Under certain conditions, each ion-forming group can be charged, forming double salts.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The two negatively charged amino acids at neutral pH are aspartate (Asp, D) and glutamate (Glu, E).
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The anionic carboxylate groups behave as Brønsted bases in most circumstances.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Enzymes in very low pH environments, like the aspartic protease pepsin in mammalian stomachs, may have catalytic aspartate or glutamate residues that act as Brønsted acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] There are three amino acids with side chains that are cations at neutral pH: arginine (Arg, R), lysine (Lys, K) and histidine (His, H).
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Arginine has a charged guanidino group and lysine a charged alkyl amino group, and are fully protonated at pH 7.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Histidine's imidazole group has a pKa of 6.0, and is only around 10% protonated at neutral pH.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Because histidine is easily found in its basic and conjugate acid forms it often participates in catalytic proton transfers in enzyme reactions.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The polar, uncharged amino acids serine (Ser, S), threonine (Thr, T), asparagine (Asn, N) and glutamine (Gln, Q) readily form hydrogen bonds with water and other amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] They do not ionize in normal conditions, a prominent exception being the catalytic serine in serine proteases.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This is an example of severe perturbation, and is not characteristic of serine residues in general.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Threonine has two chiral centers, not only the L (2*S*) chiral center at the α-carbon shared by all amino acids apart from achiral glycine, but also (3*R*) at the β-carbon.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The full stereochemical specification is (2*S*,3*R*)-L-threonine.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Because of the presence of phenolic hydroxyl group with a pKa = ~10, tyrosine is best classified as a neutral polar amino acid, but with amphipathic character that makes it less polar than classical small polar amino acid residues.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Nonpolar amino acid interactions are the primary driving force behind the processes that fold proteins into their functional three dimensional structures.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] None of these amino acids' side chains ionize easily, and therefore do not have pKas.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Several side chains are not described well by the charged, polar and hydrophobic categories.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Glycine (Gly, G) could be considered a polar amino acid since its small size means that its solubility is largely determined by the amino and carboxylate groups.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] However, the lack of any side chain provides glycine with a unique flexibility among amino acids with large ramifications to protein folding.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Cysteine (Cys, C) can also form hydrogen bonds readily, which would place it in the polar amino acid category, though it can often be found in protein structures forming covalent bonds, called disulphide bonds, with other cysteines.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] These bonds influence the folding and stability of proteins, and are essential in the formation of antibodies.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Proline (Pro, P) has an alkyl side chain and could be considered hydrophobic, but because the side chain joins back onto the alpha amino group it becomes particularly inflexible when incorporated into proteins.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Similar to glycine this influences protein structure in a way unique among amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Selenocysteine (Sec, U) is a rare amino acid not directly encoded by DNA, but is incorporated into proteins via the ribosome.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Selenocysteine has a lower redox potential compared to the similar cysteine, and participates in several unique enzymatic reactions.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (Pyl, O) is another amino acid not encoded in DNA, but synthesized into protein by ribosomes.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] It is found in archaeal species where it participates in the catalytic activity of several methyltransferases.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The 20 canonical amino acids can be classified according to their properties.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Important factors are charge, hydrophilicity or hydrophobicity, size, and functional groups.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] These properties influence protein structure and protein–protein interactions.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The water-soluble proteins tend to have their hydrophobic residues (Leu, Ile, Val, Phe, and Trp) buried in the middle of the protein, whereas hydrophilic side chains are exposed to the aqueous solvent.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] (In biochemistry, a residue refers to a specific monomer *within* the polymeric chain of a polysaccharide, protein or nucleic acid.) The integral membrane proteins tend to have outer rings of exposed hydrophobic amino acids that anchor them in the lipid bilayer.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Some peripheral membrane proteins have a patch of hydrophobic amino acids on their surface that sticks to the membrane.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In a similar fashion, proteins that have to bind to positively charged molecules have surfaces rich in negatively charged amino acids such as glutamate and aspartate, while proteins binding to negatively charged molecules have surfaces rich in positively charged amino acids like lysine and arginine.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, lysine and arginine are present in large amounts in the low-complexity regions of nucleic-acid binding proteins.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] There are various hydrophobicity scales of amino acid residues.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Some amino acids have special properties.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Cysteine can form covalent disulfide bonds to other cysteine residues.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Proline forms a cycle to the polypeptide backbone, and glycine is more flexible than other amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Glycine and proline are strongly present within low complexity regions of both eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins, whereas the opposite is the case with cysteine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, methionine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, which are highly reactive, or complex, or hydrophobic.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, a signaling protein can attach and then detach from a cell membrane, because it contains cysteine residues that can have the fatty acid palmitic acid added to them and subsequently removed.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The common natural forms of amino acids have a zwitterionic structure, with −NH+3 (−NH+2− in the case of proline) and −CO−2 functional groups attached to the same C atom, and are thus α-amino acids, and are the only ones found in proteins during translation in the ribosome.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In aqueous solution at pH close to neutrality, amino acids are energetically favored in their zwitterionic form, with a deprotonated CO−2 group and a protonated NH+3 group, because the high dielectric constant of water and its hydrogen-bonding network effectively stabilize separated charges.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Thus, the overall structure is NH+3−CHR−CO−2, and the so-called "neutral forms" −NH2−CHR−CO2H are not present to any measurable degree at physiological pH.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In strongly acidic conditions (pH below 3), the carboxylate group becomes protonated and the structure becomes an ammonio carboxylic acid, NH+3−CHR−CO2H.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This is relevant for enzymes like pepsin that are active in acidic environments such as the mammalian stomach and lysosomes, but does not significantly apply to intracellular enzymes.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In highly basic conditions (pH greater than 10, not normally seen in physiological conditions), the ammonio group is deprotonated to give NH2−CHR−CO−2.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Although various definitions of acids and bases are used in chemistry, the only one that is useful for chemistry in aqueous solution is that of Brønsted: an acid is a species that can donate a proton to another species, and a base is one that can accept a proton.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This criterion is used to label the groups in the above illustration.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The carboxylate side chains of aspartate and glutamate residues are the principal Brønsted bases in proteins.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Likewise, lysine, tyrosine and cysteine will typically act as a Brønsted acid.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Histidine under these conditions can act both as a Brønsted acid and a base.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For amino acids with uncharged side-chains the zwitterion predominates at pH values between the two p*K*a values, but coexists in equilibrium with small amounts of net negative and net positive ions.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] At the midpoint between the two p*K*a values, the trace amount of net negative and trace of net positive ions balance, so that average net charge of all forms present is zero.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This pH is known as the isoelectric point p*I*, so p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a2).
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For amino acids with charged side chains, the p*K*a of the side chain is involved.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Thus for aspartate or glutamate with negative side chains, the terminal amino group is essentially entirely in the charged form −NH+3, but this positive charge needs to be balanced by the state with just one C-terminal carboxylate group is negatively charged.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This occurs halfway between the two carboxylate p*K*a values: p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a(R)), where p*K*a(R) is the side chain p*K*a.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Similar considerations apply to other amino acids with ionizable side-chains, including not only glutamate (similar to aspartate), but also cysteine, histidine, lysine, tyrosine and arginine with positive side chains.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids have zero mobility in electrophoresis at their isoelectric point, although this behaviour is more usually exploited for peptides and proteins than single amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Zwitterionic amino acids exhibit minimal solubility at their isoelectric point, and in some cases can be isolated from aqueous solution by adjusting the pH to the appropriate isoelectric value.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Although one-letter symbols are included in the table, IUPAC–IUBMB recommend that "Use of the one-letter symbols should be restricted to the comparison of long sequences".
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In addition to the specific amino acid codes, placeholders are used in cases where chemical or crystallographic analysis of a peptide or protein cannot conclusively determine the identity of a residue.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] They are also used to summarize conserved protein sequence motifs.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The use of single letters to indicate sets of similar residues is similar to the use of abbreviation codes for degenerate bases.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In addition, many nonstandard amino acids have a specific code.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, several peptide drugs, such as Bortezomib and MG132, are artificially synthesized and retain their protecting groups, which have specific codes.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Bortezomib is Pyz–Phe–boroLeu, and MG132 is Z–Leu–Leu–Leu–al.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] To aid in the analysis of protein structure, photo-reactive amino acid analogs are available.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] These include photoleucine (**pLeu**) and photomethionine (**pMet**).
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids are the precursors to proteins.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] They join by condensation reactions to form short polymer chains called peptides or longer chains called either polypeptides or proteins.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] These chains are linear and unbranched, with each amino acid residue within the chain attached to two neighboring amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In nature, the process of making proteins encoded by RNA genetic material is called *translation* and involves the step-by-step addition of amino acids to a growing protein chain by a ribozyme that is called a ribosome.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The order in which the amino acids are added is read through the genetic code from an mRNA template, which is an RNA derived from one of the organism's genes.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] There are 22 amino acids that get naturally incorporated into polypeptides; these are called *proteinogenic amino acids* or *natural amino acids*.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Of these, 20 are encoded by the universal genetic code.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The remaining 2, selenocysteine and pyrrolysine, are incorporated into proteins by unique synthetic mechanisms.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Selenocysteine is incorporated when the mRNA being translated includes a SECIS element, which causes the UGA codon to encode selenocysteine instead of a stop codon.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine is used by some methanogenic archaea in enzymes that they use to produce methane.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] It is coded for with the codon UAG, which is normally a stop codon in other organisms.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The 20 amino acids that are encoded directly by the codons of the universal genetic code are called *standard* or *canonical* amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] A modified form of methionine (*N*-formylmethionine) is often incorporated in place of methionine as the initial amino acid of proteins in bacteria, mitochondria and plastids (including chloroplasts).
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Other amino acids are called *nonstandard* or *non-canonical*.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Most of the nonstandard amino acids are also non-proteinogenic (i.e. they cannot be incorporated into proteins during translation), but two of them are proteinogenic, as they can be incorporated translationally into proteins by exploiting information not encoded in the universal genetic code.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The two nonstandard proteinogenic amino acids are selenocysteine (present in many non-eukaryotes as well as most eukaryotes, but not coded directly by DNA) and pyrrolysine (found only in some archaea and at least one bacterium).
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The incorporation of these nonstandard amino acids is rare.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, 25 human proteins include selenocysteine in their primary structure, and the structurally characterized enzymes (selenoenzymes) employ selenocysteine as the catalytic moiety in their active sites.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine and selenocysteine are encoded via variant codons.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, selenocysteine is encoded by stop codon and SECIS element.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Aside from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids, many *non-proteinogenic* amino acids are known.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] These either are not found in proteins (for example carnitine, GABA, ornithine) or are not produced directly and in isolation by standard cellular machinery.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, hydroxyproline is synthesized from proline, and selenomethionine is produced by metabolic modification of methionine.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids that are found in proteins are formed by post-translational modification.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, e.g., the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are not found in proteins.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Examples include 2-aminoisobutyric acid and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids often occur as intermediates in the metabolic pathways for standard amino acids – for example, ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] A rare exception to the dominance of α-amino acids in biology is the β-amino acid beta alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), which is used in plants and microorganisms in the synthesis of pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), a component of coenzyme A.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Many proteinogenic and non-proteinogenic amino acids have biological functions beyond being precursors to proteins and peptides.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In humans, amino acids also have important roles in diverse biosynthetic pathways.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Defenses against herbivores in plants sometimes employ amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] However, not all of the functions of other abundant nonstandard amino acids are known.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Animals ingest amino acids in the form of protein.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The protein is broken down into its constituent amino acids in the process of digestion.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The amino acids are then used to synthesize new proteins and other nitrogenous biomolecules, or they are further catabolized through oxidation to provide a source of energy.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase; the amino group is then fed into the urea cycle.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The other product of transamidation is a keto acid that enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Of the 20 standard amino acids, nine (His, Ile, Leu, Lys, Met, Phe, Thr, Trp and Val) are called essential amino acids because the human body cannot synthesize them from other compounds at the level needed for normal growth, so they must be obtained from food.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In addition, cysteine, tyrosine, and arginine are considered semiessential amino acids, and taurine a semi-essential aminosulfonic acid in children.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Some amino acids are conditionally essential for certain ages or medical conditions.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Essential amino acids may also vary from species to species.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The metabolic pathways that synthesize these monomers are not fully developed.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to animal feed because some of the components of these feeds, such as soybeans, have low levels of some of the essential amino acids, especially of lysine, methionine, threonine, and tryptophan.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Likewise amino acids are used to chelate metal cations in order to improve the absorption of minerals from feed supplements.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The food industry is a major consumer of amino acids, especially glutamic acid, which is used as a flavor enhancer, and aspartame (aspartylphenylalanine 1-methyl ester), which is used as an artificial sweetener.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to food by manufacturers to alleviate symptoms of mineral deficiencies, such as anemia, by improving mineral absorption and reducing negative side effects from inorganic mineral supplementation.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids are low-cost feedstocks used in chiral pool synthesis as enantiomerically pure building blocks.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids are used in the synthesis of some cosmetics.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The chelating ability of amino acids is sometimes used in fertilizers to facilitate the delivery of minerals to plants in order to correct mineral deficiencies, such as iron chlorosis.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] These fertilizers are also used to prevent deficiencies from occurring and to improve the overall health of the plants.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids have been considered as components of biodegradable polymers, which have applications as environmentally friendly packaging and in medicine in drug delivery and the construction of prosthetic implants.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] An interesting example of such materials is polyaspartate, a water-soluble biodegradable polymer that may have applications in disposable diapers and agriculture.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Due to its solubility and ability to chelate metal ions, polyaspartate is also being used as a biodegradable antiscaling agent and a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The commercial production of amino acids usually relies on mutant bacteria that overproduce individual amino acids using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Some amino acids are produced by enzymatic conversions of synthetic intermediates.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] 2-Aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic acid is an intermediate in one industrial synthesis of L-cysteine for example.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Aspartic acid is produced by the addition of ammonia to fumarate using a lyase.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In plants, nitrogen is first assimilated into organic compounds in the form of glutamate, formed from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia in the mitochondrion.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For other amino acids, plants use transaminases to move the amino group from glutamate to another alpha-keto acid.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, aspartate aminotransferase converts glutamate and oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate and aspartate.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Other organisms use transaminases for amino acid synthesis, too.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Nonstandard amino acids are usually formed through modifications to standard amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, homocysteine is formed through the transsulfuration pathway or by the demethylation of methionine via the intermediate metabolite *S*-adenosylmethionine, while hydroxyproline is made by a post translational modification of proline.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Microorganisms and plants synthesize many uncommon amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, some microbes make 2-aminoisobutyric acid and lanthionine, which is a sulfide-bridged derivative of alanine.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Both of these amino acids are found in peptidic lantibiotics such as alamethicin.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] However, in plants, 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic acid is a small disubstituted cyclic amino acid that is an intermediate in the production of the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The formation of amino acids and peptides is assumed to have preceded and perhaps induced the emergence of life on earth.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids can form from simple precursors under various conditions.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Surface-based chemical metabolism of amino acids and very small compounds may have led to the build-up of amino acids, coenzymes and phosphate-based small carbon molecules.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids and similar building blocks could have been elaborated into proto-peptides, with peptides being considered key players in the origin of life.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In the famous Urey-Miller experiment, the passage of an electric arc through a mixture of methane, hydrogen, and ammonia produces a large number of amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Several hypotheses invoke the Strecker synthesis whereby hydrogen cyanide, simple aldehydes, ammonia, and water produce amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] According to a review, amino acids, and even peptides, "turn up fairly regularly in the various experimental broths that have been allowed to be cooked from simple chemicals.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This is because nucleotides are far more difficult to synthesize chemically than amino acids." For a chronological order, it suggests that there must have been a 'protein world' or at least a 'polypeptide world', possibly later followed by the 'RNA world' and the 'DNA world'.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Codon–amino acids mappings may be the biological information system at the primordial origin of life on Earth.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] While amino acids and consequently simple peptides must have formed under different experimentally probed geochemical scenarios, the transition from an abiotic world to the first life forms is to a large extent still unresolved.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids undergo the reactions expected of the constituent functional groups.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] As both the amine and carboxylic acid groups of amino acids can react to form amide bonds, one amino acid molecule can react with another and become joined through an amide linkage.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This polymerization of amino acids is what creates proteins.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This condensation reaction yields the newly formed peptide bond and a molecule of water.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In cells, this reaction does not occur directly; instead, the amino acid is first activated by attachment to a transfer RNA molecule through an ester bond.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is produced in an ATP-dependent reaction carried out by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is then a substrate for the ribosome, which catalyzes the attack of the amino group of the elongating protein chain on the ester bond.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] As a result of this mechanism, all proteins made by ribosomes are synthesized starting at their *N*-terminus and moving toward their *C*-terminus.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] However, not all peptide bonds are formed in this way.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In a few cases, peptides are synthesized by specific enzymes.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, the tripeptide glutathione is an essential part of the defenses of cells against oxidative stress.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This peptide is synthesized in two steps from free amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In the first step, gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase condenses cysteine and glutamate through a peptide bond formed between the side chain carboxyl of the glutamate (the gamma carbon of this side chain) and the amino group of the cysteine.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This dipeptide is then condensed with glycine by glutathione synthetase to form glutathione.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In chemistry, peptides are synthesized by a variety of reactions.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] One of the most-used in solid-phase peptide synthesis uses the aromatic oxime derivatives of amino acids as activated units.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] These are added in sequence onto the growing peptide chain, which is attached to a solid resin support.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Libraries of peptides are used in drug discovery through high-throughput screening.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The combination of functional groups allow amino acids to be effective polydentate ligands for metal–amino acid chelates.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The side chains of amino acids can also undergo posttranslational chemical reactions.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Degradation of an amino acid often begins with transamination, in which its amino group is transferred to α-ketoglutarate, forming glutamate.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] This process involves transaminases, often the same enzymes used in amino acid synthesis.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] In many vertebrates, the amino group is subsequently released as ammonia and converted to urea via the urea cycle for excretion.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] However, amino acid degradation can result in uric acid or ammonia instead, depending on the organism.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] For example, serine dehydratase converts serine directly to pyruvate and ammonia.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] Amino acids are bidentate ligands, forming transition metal amino acid complexes.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The total nitrogen content of organic matter is mainly formed by the amino groups in proteins.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] The total Kjeldahl nitrogen (TKN) is a measure of nitrogen widely used in the analysis of (waste) water, soil, food, feed and organic matter in general.
[src:biochemistry/amino-acid] As the name suggests, the Kjeldahl method is applied.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Biochemistry focuses on understanding the chemical basis that allows biological molecules to give rise to the processes that occur within living cells and between cells, in turn relating greatly to the understanding of tissues and organs as well as organism structure and function.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Biochemistry is closely related to molecular biology, the study of the molecular mechanisms of biological phenomena.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Much of biochemistry deals with the structures, functions, and interactions of biological macromolecules such as proteins, nucleic acids, carbohydrates, and lipids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] They provide the structure of cells and perform many of the functions associated with life.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The chemistry of the cell also depends upon the reactions of small molecules and ions.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] These can be inorganic (for example, water and metal ions) or organic (for example, the amino acids, which are used to synthesize proteins).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The mechanisms used by cells to harness energy from their environment via chemical reactions are known as metabolism.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The findings of biochemistry are applied primarily in medicine, nutrition, and agriculture.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In medicine, biochemists investigate the causes and cures of diseases.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Nutrition studies how to maintain health and wellness and also the effects of nutritional deficiencies.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In agriculture, biochemists investigate soil and fertilizers with the goal of improving crop cultivation, crop storage, and pest control.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In recent decades, biochemical principles and methods have been combined with problem-solving approaches from engineering to manipulate living systems in order to produce useful tools for research, industrial processes, and diagnosis and control of disease—the discipline of biotechnology.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] At its most comprehensive definition, biochemistry can be seen as a study of the components and composition of living things and how they come together to become life.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In this sense, the history of biochemistry may therefore go back as far as the ancient Greeks.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] However, biochemistry as a specific scientific discipline began sometime in the 19th century, or a little earlier, depending on which aspect of biochemistry is being focused on.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Many other pioneers in the field who helped to uncover the layers of complexity of biochemistry have been proclaimed founders of modern biochemistry.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Emil Fischer, who studied the chemistry of proteins, and F.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Gowland Hopkins, who studied enzymes and the dynamic nature of biochemistry, represent two examples of early biochemists.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The term "biochemistry" was first used when Vinzenz Kletzinsky (1826–1882) had his "Compendium der Biochemie" printed in Vienna in 1858; it derived from a combination of biology and chemistry.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The German chemist Carl Neuberg however is often cited to have coined the word in 1903, while some credited it to Franz Hofmeister.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] It was once generally believed that life and its materials had some essential property or substance (often referred to as the "vital principle") distinct from any found in non-living matter, and it was thought that only living beings could produce the molecules of life.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In 1828, Friedrich Wöhler published a paper on his serendipitous urea synthesis from potassium cyanate and ammonium sulfate; some regarded that as a direct overthrow of vitalism and the establishment of organic chemistry.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] However, the Wöhler synthesis has sparked controversy as some reject the death of vitalism at his hands.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Since then, biochemistry has advanced, especially since the mid-20th century, with the development of new techniques such as chromatography, X-ray diffraction, dual polarisation interferometry, NMR spectroscopy, radioisotopic labeling, electron microscopy and molecular dynamics simulations.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] These techniques allowed for the discovery and detailed analysis of many molecules and metabolic pathways of the cell, such as glycolysis and the Krebs cycle (citric acid cycle), and led to an understanding of biochemistry on a molecular level.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Another significant historic event in biochemistry is the discovery of the gene, and its role in the transfer of information in the cell.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Watson, Francis Crick, Rosalind Franklin and Maurice Wilkins were instrumental in solving DNA structure and suggesting its relationship with the genetic transfer of information.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In 1958, George Beadle and Edward Tatum received the Nobel Prize for work in fungi showing that one gene produces one enzyme.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In 1988, Colin Pitchfork was the first person convicted of murder with DNA evidence, which led to the growth of forensic science.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Mello received the 2006 Nobel Prize for discovering the role of RNA interference (RNAi) in the silencing of gene expression.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Around two dozen chemical elements are essential to various kinds of biological life.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Most rare elements on Earth are not needed by life (exceptions being selenium and iodine), while a few common ones (aluminium and titanium) are not used.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Most organisms share element needs, but there are a few differences between plants and animals.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] For example, ocean algae use bromine, but land plants and animals do not seem to need any.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] All animals require sodium, but is not an essential element for plants.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Plants need boron and silicon, but animals may not (or may need ultra-small amounts).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Just six elements—carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, calcium and phosphorus—make up almost 99% of the mass of living cells, including those in the human body (see composition of the human body for a complete list).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This short list is abbreviated **CHNOPS** (carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur) as an aid to memory.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In addition to the six major elements that compose most of the human body, humans require smaller amounts of possibly 18 more.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The four main classes of molecules in biochemistry (often called biomolecules) are carbohydrates, lipids, proteins, and nucleic acids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Many biological molecules are polymers: in this terminology, monomers are relatively small macromolecules that are linked together to create large macromolecules known as polymers.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] When monomers are linked together to synthesize a biological polymer, they undergo a process called dehydration synthesis.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Different macromolecules can assemble in larger complexes, often needed for biological activity.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Two of the main functions of carbohydrates are energy storage and providing structure.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] One of the common sugars known as glucose is a carbohydrate, but not all carbohydrates are sugars.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] There are more carbohydrates on Earth than any other known type of biomolecule; they are used to store energy and genetic information, as well as play important roles in cell to cell interactions and communications.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The simplest type of carbohydrate is a monosaccharide, which among other properties contains carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen, mostly in a ratio of 1:2:1 (generalized formula C*n*H2*n*O*n*, where *n* is at least 3).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Glucose (C6H12O6) is one of the most important carbohydrates; others include fructose (C6H12O6), the sugar commonly associated with the sweet taste of fruits, and deoxyribose (C5H10O4), a component of DNA.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] A monosaccharide can switch between acyclic (open-chain) form and a cyclic form.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The open-chain form can be turned into a ring of carbon atoms bridged by an oxygen atom created from the carbonyl group of one end and the hydroxyl group of another.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The cyclic molecule has a hemiacetal or hemiketal group, depending on whether the linear form was an aldose or a ketose.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In these cyclic forms, the ring usually has **5** or **6** atoms.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] These forms are called furanoses and pyranoses, respectively—by analogy with furan and pyran, the simplest compounds with the same carbon-oxygen ring (although they lack the carbon-carbon double bonds of these two molecules).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] For example, the aldohexose glucose may form a hemiacetal linkage between the hydroxyl on carbon 1 and the oxygen on carbon 4, yielding a molecule with a 5-membered ring, called glucofuranose.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The same reaction can take place between carbons 1 and 5 to form a molecule with a 6-membered ring, called glucopyranose.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Cyclic forms with a 7-atom ring called heptoses are rare.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Two monosaccharides can be joined by a glycosidic or ester bond into a *disaccharide* through a dehydration reaction during which a molecule of water is released.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The reverse reaction in which the glycosidic bond of a disaccharide is broken into two monosaccharides is termed *hydrolysis*.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The best-known disaccharide is sucrose or ordinary sugar, which consists of a glucose molecule and a fructose molecule joined.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Another important disaccharide is lactose found in milk, consisting of a glucose molecule and a galactose molecule.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Lactose may be hydrolysed by lactase, and deficiency in this enzyme results in lactose intolerance.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] When a few (around three to six) monosaccharides are joined, it is called an *oligosaccharide* (*oligo-* meaning "few").
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] These molecules tend to be used as markers and signals, as well as having some other uses.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Many monosaccharides joined form a polysaccharide.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] They can be joined in one long linear chain, or they may be branched.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Two of the most common polysaccharides are cellulose and glycogen, both consisting of repeating glucose monomers.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] *Cellulose* is an important structural component of plant's cell walls and *glycogen* is used as a form of energy storage in animals.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Sugar can be characterized by having reducing or non-reducing ends.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] A reducing end of a carbohydrate is a carbon atom that can be in equilibrium with the open-chain aldehyde (aldose) or keto form (ketose).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] If the joining of monomers takes place at such a carbon atom, the free hydroxy group of the pyranose or furanose form is exchanged with an OH-side-chain of another sugar, yielding a full acetal.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This prevents opening of the chain to the aldehyde or keto form and renders the modified residue non-reducing.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Lactose contains a reducing end at its glucose moiety, whereas the galactose moiety forms a full acetal with the C4-OH group of glucose.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Saccharose does not have a reducing end because of full acetal formation between the aldehyde carbon of glucose (C1) and the keto carbon of fructose (C2).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Lipids are usually made from one molecule of glycerol combined with other molecules.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In triglycerides, the main group of bulk lipids, there is one molecule of glycerol and three fatty acids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Fatty acids are considered the monomer in that case, and may be saturated (no double bonds in the carbon chain) or unsaturated (one or more double bonds in the carbon chain).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Most lipids have some polar character and are largely nonpolar.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In general, the bulk of their structure is nonpolar or hydrophobic ("water-fearing"), meaning that it does not interact well with polar solvents like water.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Another part of their structure is polar or hydrophilic ("water-loving") and will tend to associate with polar solvents like water.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This makes them amphiphilic molecules (having both hydrophobic and hydrophilic portions).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In the case of cholesterol, the polar group is a mere –OH (hydroxyl or alcohol).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In the case of phospholipids, the polar groups are considerably larger and more polar, as described below.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Lipids are an integral part of our daily diet.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Most oils and milk products that we use for cooking and eating like butter, cheese, ghee etc. are composed of fats.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Vegetable oils are rich in various polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFA).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Lipid-containing foods undergo digestion within the body and are broken into fatty acids and glycerol, the final degradation products of fats and lipids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Lipids, especially phospholipids, are also used in various pharmaceutical products, either as co-solubilizers (e.g. in parenteral infusions) or else as drug carrier components (e.g. in a liposome or transfersome).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Proteins are very large molecules—macro-biopolymers—made from monomers called amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] An amino acid consists of an alpha carbon atom attached to an amino group, –NH2, a carboxylic acid group, –COOH (although these exist as –NH3+ and –COO− under physiologic conditions), a simple hydrogen atom, and a side chain commonly denoted as "–R".
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The side chain "R" is different for each amino acid of which there are 20 standard ones.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] It is this "R" group that makes each amino acid different, and the properties of the side chains greatly influence the overall three-dimensional conformation of a protein.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Some amino acids have functions by themselves or in a modified form; for instance, glutamate functions as an important neurotransmitter.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Amino acids can be joined via a peptide bond.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In this dehydration synthesis, a water molecule is removed and the peptide bond connects the nitrogen of one amino acid's amino group to the carbon of the other's carboxylic acid group.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The resulting molecule is called a *dipeptide*, and short stretches of amino acids (usually, fewer than thirty) are called *peptides* or polypeptides.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Longer stretches merit the title *proteins*.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] As an example, the important blood serum protein albumin contains 585 amino acid residues.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Proteins can have structural and/or functional roles.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] For instance, movements of the proteins actin and myosin ultimately are responsible for the contraction of skeletal muscle.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] One property many proteins have is that they specifically bind to a certain molecule or class of molecules—they may be *extremely* selective in what they bind.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Antibodies are an example of proteins that attach to one specific type of molecule.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Antibodies are composed of heavy and light chains.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Two heavy chains would be linked to two light chains through disulfide linkages between their amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Antibodies are specific through variation based on differences in the N-terminal domain.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA), which uses antibodies, is one of the most sensitive tests modern medicine uses to detect various biomolecules.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Probably the most important proteins, however, are the enzymes.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Virtually every reaction in a living cell requires an enzyme to lower the activation energy of the reaction.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] These molecules recognize specific reactant molecules called *substrates*; they then catalyze the reaction between them.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] By lowering the activation energy, the enzyme speeds up that reaction by a rate of 1011 or more; a reaction that would normally take over 3,000 years to complete spontaneously might take less than a second with an enzyme.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The enzyme itself is not used up in the process and is free to catalyze the same reaction with a new set of substrates.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Using various modifiers, the activity of the enzyme can be regulated, enabling control of the biochemistry of the cell as a whole.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The structure of proteins is traditionally described in a hierarchy of four levels.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The primary structure of a protein consists of its linear sequence of amino acids; for instance, "alanine-glycine-tryptophan-serine-glutamate-asparagine-glycine-lysine-...".
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Secondary structure is concerned with local morphology (morphology being the study of structure).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Some combinations of amino acids will tend to curl up in a coil called an α-helix or into a sheet called a β-sheet; some α-helixes can be seen in the hemoglobin schematic above.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Tertiary structure is the entire three-dimensional shape of the protein.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This shape is determined by the sequence of amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In fact, a single change can change the entire structure.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The alpha chain of hemoglobin contains 146 amino acid residues; substitution of the glutamate residue at position 6 with a valine residue changes the behavior of hemoglobin so much that it results in sickle-cell disease.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Finally, quaternary structure is concerned with the structure of a protein with multiple peptide subunits, like hemoglobin with its four subunits.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Not all proteins have more than one subunit.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Ingested proteins are usually broken up into single amino acids or dipeptides in the small intestine and then absorbed.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] They can then be joined to form new proteins.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Intermediate products of glycolysis, the citric acid cycle, and the pentose phosphate pathway can be used to form all twenty amino acids, and most bacteria and plants possess all the necessary enzymes to synthesize them.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Humans and other mammals, however, can synthesize only half of them.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] They cannot synthesize isoleucine, leucine, lysine, methionine, phenylalanine, threonine, tryptophan, and valine.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Because they must be ingested, these are the essential amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Mammals do possess the enzymes to synthesize alanine, asparagine, aspartate, cysteine, glutamate, glutamine, glycine, proline, serine, and tyrosine, the nonessential amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] While they can synthesize arginine and histidine, they cannot produce it in sufficient amounts for young, growing animals, and so these are often considered essential amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] If the amino group is removed from an amino acid, it leaves behind a carbon skeleton called an α-keto acid.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Enzymes called transaminases can easily transfer the amino group from one amino acid (making it an α-keto acid) to another α-keto acid (making it an amino acid).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This is important in the biosynthesis of amino acids, as for many of the pathways, intermediates from other biochemical pathways are converted to the α-keto acid skeleton, and then an amino group is added, often via transamination.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The amino acids may then be linked together to form a protein.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] A similar process is used to break down proteins.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] It is first hydrolyzed into its component amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Free ammonia (NH3), existing as the ammonium ion (NH4+) in blood, is toxic to life forms.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] A suitable method for excreting it must therefore exist.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Different tactics have evolved in different animals, depending on the animals' needs.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Unicellular organisms release the ammonia into the environment.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Likewise, bony fish can release ammonia into the water where it is quickly diluted.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In general, mammals convert ammonia into urea, via the urea cycle.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In order to determine whether two proteins are related, or in other words to decide whether they are homologous or not, scientists use sequence-comparison methods.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Methods like sequence alignments and structural alignments are powerful tools that help scientists identify homologies between related molecules.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The relevance of finding homologies among proteins goes beyond forming an evolutionary pattern of protein families.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] By finding how similar two protein sequences are, we acquire knowledge about their structure and therefore their function.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Nucleic acids, so-called because of their prevalence in cellular nuclei, is the generic name of the family of biopolymers.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] They are complex, high-molecular-weight biochemical macromolecules that can convey genetic information in all living cells and viruses.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The monomers are called nucleotides, and each consists of three components: a nitrogenous heterocyclic base (either a purine or a pyrimidine), a pentose sugar, and a phosphate group.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The most common nucleic acids are deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) and ribonucleic acid (RNA).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The phosphate group and the sugar of each nucleotide bond with each other to form the backbone of the nucleic acid, while the sequence of nitrogenous bases stores the information.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The most common nitrogenous bases are adenine, cytosine, guanine, thymine, and uracil.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The nitrogenous bases of each strand of a nucleic acid will form hydrogen bonds with certain other nitrogenous bases in a complementary strand of nucleic acid.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Adenine binds with thymine and uracil, thymine binds only with adenine, and cytosine and guanine can bind only with one another.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Adenine, thymine, and uracil contain two hydrogen bonds, while hydrogen bonds formed between cytosine and guanine are three.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Aside from the genetic material of the cell, nucleic acids often play a role as second messengers, as well as forming the base molecule for adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the primary energy-carrier molecule found in all living organisms.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Also, the nitrogenous bases possible in the two nucleic acids are different: adenine, cytosine, and guanine occur in both RNA and DNA, while thymine occurs only in DNA and uracil occurs in RNA.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Glucose is an energy source in most life forms.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] For instance, polysaccharides are broken down into their monomers by enzymes (glycogen phosphorylase removes glucose residues from glycogen, a polysaccharide).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Disaccharides like lactose or sucrose are cleaved into their two component monosaccharides.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Glucose is mainly metabolized by a very important ten-step pathway called glycolysis, the net result of which is to break down one molecule of glucose into two molecules of pyruvate.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This also produces a net two molecules of ATP, the energy currency of cells, along with two reducing equivalents of converting NAD+ (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide: oxidized form) to NADH (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide: reduced form).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This does not require oxygen; if no oxygen is available (or the cell cannot use oxygen), the NAD is restored by converting the pyruvate to lactate (lactic acid) (e.g. in humans) or to ethanol plus carbon dioxide (e.g. in yeast).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Other monosaccharides like galactose and fructose can be converted into intermediates of the glycolytic pathway.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In aerobic cells with sufficient oxygen, as in most human cells, the pyruvate is further metabolized.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] It is irreversibly converted to acetyl-CoA, giving off one carbon atom as the waste product carbon dioxide, generating another reducing equivalent as NADH.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The two molecules acetyl-CoA (from one molecule of glucose) then enter the citric acid cycle, producing two molecules of ATP, six more NADH molecules and two reduced (ubi)quinones (via FADH2 as enzyme-bound cofactor), and releasing the remaining carbon atoms as carbon dioxide.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Thus, oxygen is reduced to water and the original electron acceptors NAD+ and quinone are regenerated.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This is why humans breathe in oxygen and breathe out carbon dioxide.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The energy released from transferring the electrons from high-energy states in NADH and quinol is conserved first as proton gradient and converted to ATP via ATP synthase.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This generates an additional *28* molecules of ATP (24 from the 8 NADH + 4 from the 2 quinols), totaling to 32 molecules of ATP conserved per degraded glucose (two from glycolysis + two from the citrate cycle).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] It is clear that using oxygen to completely oxidize glucose provides an organism with far more energy than any oxygen-independent metabolic feature, and this is thought to be the reason why complex life appeared only after Earth's atmosphere accumulated large amounts of oxygen.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] In vertebrates, vigorously contracting skeletal muscles (during weightlifting or sprinting, for example) do not receive enough oxygen to meet the energy demand, and so they shift to anaerobic metabolism, converting glucose to lactate.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The combination of glucose from noncarbohydrates origin, such as fat and proteins.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This only happens when glycogen supplies in the liver are worn out.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The pathway is a crucial reversal of glycolysis from pyruvate to glucose and can use many sources like amino acids, glycerol and Krebs Cycle.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Large scale protein and fat catabolism usually occur when those suffer from starvation or certain endocrine disorders.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The liver regenerates the glucose, using a process called gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] This process is not quite the opposite of glycolysis, and actually requires three times the amount of energy gained from glycolysis (six molecules of ATP are used, compared to the two gained in glycolysis).
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Analogous to the above reactions, the glucose produced can then undergo glycolysis in tissues that need energy, be stored as glycogen (or starch in plants), or be converted to other monosaccharides or joined into di- or oligosaccharides.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] The combined pathways of glycolysis during exercise, lactate's crossing via the bloodstream to the liver, subsequent gluconeogenesis and release of glucose into the bloodstream is called the Cori cycle.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Researchers in biochemistry use specific techniques native to biochemistry, but increasingly combine these with techniques and ideas developed in the fields of genetics, molecular biology, and biophysics.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] There is not a defined line between these disciplines.
[src:biochemistry/biochemistry] Biochemistry studies the chemistry required for biological activity of molecules, molecular biology studies their biological activity, genetics studies their heredity, which happens to be carried by their genome.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] A **carbohydrate** (/ˌkɑːrboʊˈhaɪdreɪt/) is a sugar (saccharide) or a sugar derivative.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] For the simplest carbohydrates, the carbon-to-hydrogen-to-oxygen atomic ratio is 1:2:1, i.e. they are often represented by the empirical formula (CH2O)*n*.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Together with amino acids, fats, and nucleic acids, the carbohydrates are one of the major families of biomolecules.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Carbohydrates perform numerous roles in living organisms.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Polysaccharides serve as an energy store (e.g., starch and glycogen) and as structural components (e.g., cellulose in plants and chitin in arthropods and fungi).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The 5-carbon monosaccharide ribose is an important component of coenzymes (e.g., ATP, FAD and NAD) and the backbone of the genetic molecule known as RNA.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The related deoxyribose is a component of DNA.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Saccharides and their derivatives play key roles in the immune system, fertilization, preventing pathogenesis, blood clotting, and development.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Carbohydrates are central to nutrition and are found in a wide variety of natural and processed foods.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Starch is a polysaccharide and is abundant in cereals (wheat, maize, rice), potatoes, and processed food based on cereal flour, such as bread, pizza or pasta.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Sugars appear in the human diet mainly as table sugar (sucrose, extracted from sugarcane or sugar beets), lactose (abundant in milk), glucose and fructose, both of which occur naturally in honey, many fruits, and some vegetables.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Table sugar, milk, or honey is often added to drinks and many prepared foods such as jam, biscuits, scones and cakes.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The term "carbohydrate" has many synonyms and the definition can depend on context.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Terms associated with carbohydrate include "sugar", "saccharide", "glucan", and "glucide".
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] In food science the term "carbohydrate" often means any food that is rich in starch (such as cereals, bread and pasta) or simple carbohydrates, or fairly simple sugars such as sucrose (found in candy, jams, and desserts).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Carbohydrates can also refer to dietary fiber, like cellulose.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The starting point for the discussion of carbohydrates is the saccharides.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Monosaccharides are the simplest carbohydrates in that they cannot be hydrolyzed to smaller carbohydrates.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Monosaccharides usually have the formula C*m* (H2O)*n*.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Disaccharides (e.g. sucrose) are common as are polysaccharides/oligosaccharides (e.g., starch, cellulose).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Saccharides are polyhydroxy aldehydes, ketones as well as derived polymers having linkages of the acetal type.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] They may be classified according to their degree of polymerization.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Many polyols are also classified as carbohydrates.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] In many carbohydrates the OH groups are appended to or replaced by *N*-acetyl (e.g., chitin), sulfate (e.g., glycosaminoglycans), carboxylic acid and deoxy modifications (e.g., fucose and sialic acid).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Sugars may be linked to other types of biological molecules to form glycoconjugates.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The enzymatic process of glycosylation creates sugars/saccharides linked to themselves and to other molecules by the glycosidic bond, thereby producing glycans.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Glycoproteins, proteoglycans and glycolipids are the most abundant glycoconjugates found in mammalian cells.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] They are found predominantly on the outer cell membrane and in secreted fluids.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Glycoconjugates have been shown to be important in cell-cell interactions due to the presence on the cell surface of various glycan binding receptors in addition to the glycoconjugates themselves.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] In addition to their function in protein folding and cellular attachment, the N-linked glycans of a protein can modulate the protein's function, in some cases acting as an on-off switch.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The history of carbohydrates, to some extent, is the history of sugar cane, which was first grown in New Guinea.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The mass cultivation occurred in India where techniques were developed for the isolation of crystalline sugar.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Cane sugar and its cultivation reached Europe around the 13th Century and then expanded to the New World, where industrialization occurred.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The chemistry and biochemistry of carbohydrates can be traced to 1811.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] On that year Constantin Kirchhoff discovered that grape sugar (glucose) forms when starch is boiled with acid.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The starch industry started the following year.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Henri Braconnot discovered in 1819 that sugar is formed through the action of sulfuric acid on cellulose.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] William Prout, after chemical analyses of sugar and starch by Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac and Thénard, gave this group of substances the group name "saccharine." The term "carbohydrate" was first proposed by German chemist Carl Schmidt in 1844.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] In 1856, glycogen, a form of carbohydrate storage in animal livers, was discovered by French physiologist Claude Bernard.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Emil Fischer received the 1902 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his work on sugars and purines.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] For the discovery of glucose metabolism, Otto Meyerhof received the 1922 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] For the discovery of sugar nucleotides in carbohydrate biosynthesis, Luis Leloir received the 1970 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The term *glycobiology* was coined in 1988 by Raymond Dwek to recognize the coming together of the traditional disciplines of carbohydrate chemistry and biochemistry.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] This coming together was as a result of a much greater understanding of the cellular and molecular biology of glycans.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] "Glycoscience" is a field that explores the structures and functions of glycans.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Carbohydrate consumed in food yields 3.87 kilocalories of energy per gram for simple sugars, and 3.57 to 4.12 kilocalories per gram for complex carbohydrate in most other foods.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Relatively high levels of carbohydrate are associated with processed foods or refined foods made from plants, including sweets, cookies and candy, table sugar, honey, soft drinks, breads and crackers, jams and fruit products, pastas and breakfast cereals.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Refined carbohydrates from processed foods such as white bread or rice, soft drinks, and desserts are readily digestible, and many are known to have a high glycemic index, which reflects a rapid assimilation of glucose.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] By contrast, the digestion of whole, unprocessed, fiber-rich foods such as beans, peas, and whole grains produces a slower and steadier release of glucose and energy into the body.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Animal-based foods generally have the lowest carbohydrate levels, although milk does contain a high proportion of lactose.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Organisms typically cannot metabolize all types of carbohydrate to yield energy.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Glucose is a nearly universal and accessible source of energy.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Many organisms also have the ability to metabolize other monosaccharides and disaccharides but glucose is often metabolized first.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] In *Escherichia coli*, for example, the lac operon will express enzymes for the digestion of lactose when it is present, but if both lactose and glucose are present, the *lac* operon is repressed, resulting in the glucose being used first (see: Diauxie).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Polysaccharides are also common sources of energy.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Many organisms can easily break down starches into glucose; most organisms, however, cannot metabolize cellulose or other polysaccharides such as chitin and arabinoxylans.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] These carbohydrate types can be metabolized by some bacteria and protists.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Ruminants and termites, for example, use microorganisms to process cellulose, fermenting it to caloric short-chain fatty acids.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Even though humans lack the enzymes to digest fiber, dietary fiber represents an important dietary element for humans.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Fibers promote healthy digestion, help regulate postprandial glucose and insulin levels, reduce cholesterol levels, and promote satiety.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The Institute of Medicine recommends that American and Canadian adults get between 45 and 65% of dietary energy from whole-grain carbohydrates.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The Food and Agriculture Organization and World Health Organization jointly recommend that national dietary guidelines set a goal of 55–75% of total energy from carbohydrates, but only 10% directly from sugars (their term for simple carbohydrates).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] A 2017 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that there was insufficient evidence to support the claim that whole grain diets can affect cardiovascular disease.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Carbohydrates are one of the main components of insoluble dietary fiber.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Although it is not digestible by humans, cellulose and insoluble dietary fiber generally help maintain a healthy digestive system by facilitating bowel movements.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Other polysaccharides contained in dietary fiber include resistant starch and inulin, which feed some bacteria in the microbiota of the large intestine, and are metabolized by these bacteria to yield short-chain fatty acids.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The term *complex carbohydrate* was first used in the U.S.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Senate Select Committee on Nutrition and Human Needs publication *Dietary Goals for the United States* (1977) where it was intended to distinguish sugars from other carbohydrates (which were perceived to be nutritionally superior).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] However, the report put "fruit, vegetables and whole-grains" in the complex carbohydrate column, despite the fact that these may contain sugars as well as polysaccharides.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The standard usage, however, is to classify carbohydrates chemically: *simple* if they are sugars (monosaccharides and disaccharides) and *complex* if they are polysaccharides (or oligosaccharides).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Carbohydrates are sometimes divided into "available carbohydrates", which are absorbed in the small intestine and "unavailable carbohydrates", which pass to the large intestine, where they are subject to fermentation by the gastrointestinal microbiota.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The glycemic index (GI) and glycemic load concepts characterize the potential for carbohydrates in food to raise blood glucose compared to a reference food (generally pure glucose).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Expressed numerically as GI, carbohydrate-containing foods can be grouped as high-GI (score more than 70), moderate-GI (56–69), or low-GI (less than 55) relative to pure glucose (GI=100).
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Consumption of carbohydrate-rich, high-GI foods causes an abrupt increase in blood glucose concentration that declines rapidly following the meal, whereas low-GI foods with lower carbohydrate content produces a lower blood glucose concentration that returns gradually after the meal.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Glycemic load is a measure relating the quality of carbohydrates in a food (low- vs. high-carbohydrate content – the GI) by the amount of carbohydrates in a single serving of that food.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Low-carbohydrate diets may miss the health advantages – such as increased intake of dietary fiber and phytochemicals – afforded by high-quality plant foods such as legumes and pulses, whole grains, fruits, and vegetables.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] A "meta-analysis, of moderate quality," included as adverse effects of the diet halitosis, headache and constipation.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Carbohydrate-restricted diets can be as effective as low-fat diets in helping achieve weight loss over the short term when overall calorie intake is reduced.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The reasoning of diet advocates that carbohydrates cause undue fat accumulation by increasing blood insulin levels, but a more balanced diet that restricts refined carbohydrates can also reduce serum glucose and insulin levels and may also suppress lipogenesis and promote fat oxidation.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] However, as far as energy expenditure itself is concerned, the claim that low-carbohydrate diets have a "metabolic advantage" is not supported by clinical evidence.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Further, it is not clear how low-carbohydrate dieting affects cardiovascular health, although two reviews showed that carbohydrate restriction may improve lipid markers of cardiovascular disease risk.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Carbohydrate-restricted diets are no more effective than a conventional healthy diet in preventing the onset of type 2 diabetes, but for people with type 2 diabetes, they are a viable option for losing weight or helping with glycemic control.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] There is limited evidence to support routine use of low-carbohydrate dieting in managing type 1 diabetes.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The American Diabetes Association recommends that people with diabetes should adopt a generally healthy diet, rather than a diet focused on carbohydrate or other macronutrients.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] An extreme form of low-carbohydrate diet – the ketogenic diet – is established as a medical diet for treating epilepsy.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] Through celebrity endorsement during the early 21st century, it became a fad diet as a means of weight loss, but with risks of undesirable side effects, such as low energy levels and increased hunger, insomnia, nausea, and gastrointestinal discomfort.
[src:biochemistry/carbohydrate] The British Dietetic Association named it one of the "top 5 worst celeb diets to avoid in 2018".
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The **citric acid cycle**—also known as the **Krebs cycle**, **Szent–Györgyi–Krebs cycle**, or **TCA cycle** (**tricarboxylic acid cycle**)—is a series of biochemical reactions that release the energy stored in nutrients through acetyl-CoA oxidation.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The energy released is available in the form of ATP.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The Krebs cycle is used by organisms that generate energy via respiration, either anaerobically or aerobically (organisms that ferment use different pathways).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In addition, the cycle provides precursors of certain amino acids, as well as the reducing agent NADH, which are used in other reactions.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Its central importance to many biochemical pathways suggests that it was one of the earliest metabolic components.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Even though it is branded as a "cycle", it is not necessary for metabolites to follow a specific route; at least three alternative pathways of the citric acid cycle are recognized.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Its name is derived from the citric acid (a tricarboxylic acid, often called citrate, as the ionized form predominates at biological pH) that is consumed and then regenerated by this sequence of reactions.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The cycle consumes acetate (in the form of acetyl-CoA) and water and reduces NAD+ to NADH, releasing carbon dioxide.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The NADH generated by the citric acid cycle is fed into the oxidative phosphorylation (electron transport) pathway.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The net result of these two closely linked pathways is the oxidation of nutrients to produce usable chemical energy in the form of ATP.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In eukaryotic cells, the citric acid cycle occurs in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In prokaryotic cells, such as bacteria, which lack mitochondria, the citric acid cycle reaction sequence is performed in the cytosol with the proton gradient for ATP production being across the cell's surface (plasma membrane) rather than the inner membrane of the mitochondrion.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] For each pyruvate molecule (from glycolysis), the overall yield of energy-containing compounds from the citric acid cycle is three NADH, one FADH2, and one GTP or ATP.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Several of the components and reactions of the citric acid cycle were established in the 1930s by the research of Albert Szent-Györgyi, who received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1937 specifically for his discoveries pertaining to fumaric acid, a component of the cycle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] He made this discovery by studying pigeon breast muscle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Because this tissue maintains its oxidative capacity well after breaking down in the Latapie mincer and releasing in aqueous solutions, breast muscle of the pigeon was very well qualified for the study of oxidative reactions.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The citric acid cycle itself was finally identified in 1937 by Hans Adolf Krebs and William Arthur Johnson while at the University of Sheffield, for which the former received the Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine in 1953, and for whom the cycle is sometimes named the "Krebs cycle".
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Independently citric acid cycle was identified in 1937 by German biochemists Carl Martius and Franz Knoop.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The citric acid cycle is a metabolic pathway that connects carbohydrate, fat, and protein metabolism.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The reactions of the cycle are carried out by eight enzymes that completely oxidize acetate (a two carbon molecule), in the form of acetyl-CoA, into two molecules each of carbon dioxide.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Through catabolism of sugars, fats, and proteins, the two-carbon organic product acetyl-CoA is produced which enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The NADH and FADH2 generated by the citric acid cycle are, in turn, used by the oxidative phosphorylation pathway to generate energy-rich ATP.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The product of this reaction, acetyl-CoA, is the starting point for the citric acid cycle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Acetyl-CoA may also be obtained from the oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] There are ten basic steps in the citric acid cycle, as outlined below.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The cycle is continuously supplied with new carbon in the form of acetyl-CoA, entering at step 0 in the table.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Two carbon atoms are oxidized to CO2, the energy from these reactions is transferred to other metabolic processes through GTP (or ATP), and as electrons in NADH and QH2.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The NADH generated in the citric acid cycle may later be oxidized (donate its electrons) to drive ATP synthesis in a type of process called oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] FADH2 is covalently attached to succinate dehydrogenase, an enzyme which functions both in the citric acid cycle and the mitochondrial electron transport chain in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] FADH2, therefore, facilitates transfer of electrons to coenzyme Q, which is the final electron acceptor of the reaction catalyzed by the succinate:ubiquinone oxidoreductase complex, also acting as an intermediate in the electron transport chain.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Mitochondria in animal cells, possess two succinyl-CoA synthetases: one that produces GTP from GDP, and another that produces ATP from ADP.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Plant cells have the type that produces ATP (ADP-forming succinyl-CoA synthetase).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Several of the enzymes in the cycle may be loosely associated in a multienzyme protein complex within the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The GTP that is formed by GDP-forming succinyl-CoA synthetase may be utilized by nucleoside-diphosphate kinase to form ATP (the catalyzed reaction is GTP + ADP → GDP + ATP).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Products of the first turn of the cycle are one GTP (or ATP), three NADH, one FADH2 and two CO2.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Because two acetyl-CoA molecules are produced from each glucose molecule, two cycles are required per glucose molecule.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Therefore, at the end of two cycles, the products are: two GTP, six NADH, two FADH2, and four CO2.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The above reactions are balanced if Pi represents the H2PO4− ion, ADP and GDP the ADP2− and GDP2− ions, respectively, and ATP and GTP the ATP3− and GTP3− ions, respectively.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The total number of ATP molecules obtained after complete oxidation of one glucose in glycolysis, citric acid cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation is estimated to be between 30 and 38.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The theoretical maximum yield of ATP through oxidation of one molecule of glucose in glycolysis, citric acid cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation is 38 (assuming 3 molar equivalents of ATP per equivalent NADH and 2 ATP per FADH2).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In eukaryotes, two equivalents of NADH and two equivalents of ATP are generated in glycolysis, which takes place in the cytoplasm.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] If transported using the glycerol phosphate shuttle rather than the malate–aspartate shuttle, transport of two of these equivalents of NADH into the mitochondria effectively consumes two equivalents of ATP, thus reducing the net production of ATP to 36.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Furthermore, inefficiencies in oxidative phosphorylation due to leakage of protons across the mitochondrial membrane and slippage of the ATP synthase/proton pump commonly reduces the ATP yield from NADH and FADH2 to less than the theoretical maximum yield.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The observed yields are, therefore, closer to ~2.5 ATP per NADH and ~1.5 ATP per FADH2, further reducing the total net production of ATP to approximately 30.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] An assessment of the total ATP yield with newly revised proton-to-ATP ratios provides an estimate of 29.85 ATP per glucose molecule.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] While the citric acid cycle is in general highly conserved, there is significant variability in the enzymes found in different taxa (note that the diagrams on this page are specific to the mammalian pathway variant).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Some differences exist between eukaryotes and prokaryotes.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The conversion of D-*threo*-isocitrate to 2-oxoglutarate (α-ketoglutarate) is catalyzed in eukaryotes by the NAD+-dependent EC 1.1.1.41, while prokaryotes employ the NADP+-dependent EC 1.1.1.42.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Similarly, the conversion of (*S*)-malate to oxaloacetate is catalyzed in eukaryotes by the NAD+-dependent EC 1.1.1.37, while most prokaryotes utilize a quinone-dependent enzyme, EC 1.1.5.4.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] A step with significant variability is the conversion of succinyl-CoA to succinate.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Most organisms utilize EC 6.2.1.5, succinate–CoA ligase (ADP-forming) (despite its name, the enzyme operates in the pathway in the direction of ATP formation).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In mammals a GTP-forming enzyme, succinate–CoA ligase (GDP-forming) (EC 6.2.1.4) also operates.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The level of utilization of each isoform is tissue dependent.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In some acetate-producing bacteria, such as *Acetobacter aceti*, an entirely different enzyme catalyzes this conversion – EC 2.8.3.18, succinyl-CoA:acetate CoA-transferase.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] This specialized enzyme links the TCA cycle with acetate metabolism in these organisms.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Some bacteria, such as *Helicobacter pylori*, employ yet another enzyme for this conversion – succinyl-CoA:acetoacetate CoA-transferase (EC 2.8.3.5).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Some variability also exists at the previous step – the conversion of 2-oxoglutarate to succinyl-CoA.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] While most organisms utilize the ubiquitous NAD+-dependent 2-oxoglutarate dehydrogenase, some bacteria utilize a ferredoxin-dependent 2-oxoglutarate synthase (EC 1.2.7.3).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Other organisms, including obligately autotrophic and methanotrophic bacteria and archaea, bypass succinyl-CoA entirely, and convert 2-oxoglutarate to succinate via succinate semialdehyde, using EC 4.1.1.71, 2-oxoglutarate decarboxylase, and EC 1.2.1.79, succinate-semialdehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In cancer, there are substantial metabolic derangements that occur to ensure the proliferation of tumor cells, and consequently metabolites can accumulate which serve to facilitate tumorigenesis, dubbed oncometabolites.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In cancer, 2-hydroxyglutarate serves as a competitive inhibitor for a number of enzymes that facilitate reactions via alpha-ketoglutarate in alpha-ketoglutarate-dependent dioxygenases.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] This mutation results in several important changes to the metabolism of the cell.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] For one thing, because there is an extra NADPH-catalyzed reduction, this can contribute to depletion of cellular stores of NADPH and also reduce levels of alpha-ketoglutarate available to the cell.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In particular, the depletion of NADPH is problematic because NADPH is highly compartmentalized and cannot freely diffuse between the organelles in the cell.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] It is produced largely via the pentose phosphate pathway in the cytoplasm.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The depletion of NADPH results in increased oxidative stress within the cell as it is a required cofactor in the production of GSH, and this oxidative stress can result in DNA damage.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] There are also changes on the genetic and epigenetic level through the function of histone lysine demethylases (KDMs) and ten-eleven translocation (TET) enzymes; ordinarily TETs hydroxylate 5-methylcytosines to prime them for demethylation.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] However, in the absence of alpha-ketoglutarate this cannot be done and there is hence hypermethylation of the cell's DNA, serving to promote epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) and inhibit cellular differentiation.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] A similar phenomenon is observed for the Jumonji C family of KDMs which require a hydroxylation to perform demethylation at the epsilon-amino methyl group.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Additionally, the inability of prolyl hydroxylases to catalyze reactions results in stabilization of hypoxia-inducible factor alpha, which is necessary to promote degradation of the latter (as under conditions of low oxygen there will not be adequate substrate for hydroxylation).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] This results in a pseudohypoxic phenotype in the cancer cell that promotes angiogenesis, metabolic reprogramming, cell growth, and migration.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Several catabolic pathways converge on the citric acid cycle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Most of these reactions add intermediates to the citric acid cycle, and are therefore known as anaplerotic reactions, from the Greek meaning to "fill up".
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] These increase the amount of acetyl CoA that the cycle is able to carry, increasing the mitochondrion's capability to carry out respiration if this is otherwise a limiting factor.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Processes that remove intermediates from the cycle are termed "cataplerotic" reactions.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In this section and in the next, the citric acid cycle intermediates are indicated in *italics* to distinguish them from other substrates and end-products.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Pyruvate molecules produced by glycolysis are actively transported across the inner mitochondrial membrane, and into the matrix.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Here they can be oxidized and combined with coenzyme A to form CO2, *acetyl-CoA*, and NADH, as in the normal cycle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] However, it is also possible for pyruvate to be carboxylated by pyruvate carboxylase to form *oxaloacetate*.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] This latter reaction "fills up" the amount of *oxaloacetate* in the citric acid cycle, and is therefore an anaplerotic reaction, increasing the cycle's capacity to metabolize *acetyl-CoA* when the tissue's energy needs (e.g. in muscle) are suddenly increased by activity.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In the citric acid cycle all the intermediates (e.g.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] *citrate*, *iso-citrate*, *alpha-ketoglutarate*, *succinate*, *fumarate*, *malate*, and *oxaloacetate*) are regenerated during each turn of the cycle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Adding more of any of these intermediates to the mitochondrion therefore means that that additional amount is retained within the cycle, increasing all the other intermediates as one is converted into the other.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Hence the addition of any one of them to the cycle has an anaplerotic effect, and its removal has a cataplerotic effect.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] These anaplerotic and cataplerotic reactions will, during the course of the cycle, increase or decrease the amount of *oxaloacetate* available to combine with *acetyl-CoA* to form *citric acid*.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] This in turn increases or decreases the rate of ATP production by the mitochondrion, and thus the availability of ATP to the cell.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In the liver, the carboxylation of cytosolic pyruvate into intra-mitochondrial *oxaloacetate* is an early step in the gluconeogenic pathway which converts lactate and de-aminated alanine into glucose, under the influence of high levels of glucagon and/or epinephrine in the blood.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In protein catabolism, proteins are broken down by proteases into their constituent amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Their carbon skeletons (i.e. the de-aminated amino acids) may either enter the citric acid cycle as intermediates (e.g.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] These are the so-called "glucogenic" amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] De-aminated alanine, cysteine, glycine, serine, and threonine are converted to pyruvate and can consequently either enter the citric acid cycle as *oxaloacetate* (an anaplerotic reaction) or as *acetyl-CoA* to be disposed of as CO2 and water.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In fat catabolism, triglycerides are hydrolyzed to break them into fatty acids and glycerol.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In the liver the glycerol can be converted into glucose via dihydroxyacetone phosphate and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate by way of gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In skeletal muscle, glycerol is used in glycolysis by converting glycerol into glycerol-3-phosphate, then into dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP), then into glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In many tissues, especially heart and skeletal muscle tissue, fatty acids are broken down through a process known as beta oxidation, which results in the production of mitochondrial *acetyl-CoA*, which can be used in the citric acid cycle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Beta oxidation of fatty acids with an odd number of methylene bridges produces propionyl-CoA, which is then converted into *succinyl-CoA* and fed into the citric acid cycle as an anaplerotic intermediate.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The total energy gained from the complete breakdown of one (six-carbon) molecule of glucose by glycolysis, the formation of 2 *acetyl-CoA* molecules, their catabolism in the citric acid cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation equals about 30 ATP molecules, in eukaryotes.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The number of ATP molecules derived from the beta oxidation of a 6 carbon segment of a fatty acid chain, and the subsequent oxidation of the resulting 3 molecules of *acetyl-CoA* is 40.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In this subheading, as in the previous one, the TCA intermediates are identified by *italics*.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Several of the citric acid cycle intermediates are used for the synthesis of important compounds, which will have significant cataplerotic effects on the cycle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] *Acetyl-CoA* cannot be transported out of the mitochondrion.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] To obtain cytosolic acetyl-CoA, *citrate* is removed from the citric acid cycle and carried across the inner mitochondrial membrane into the cytosol.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] There it is cleaved by ATP citrate lyase into acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The oxaloacetate is returned to mitochondrion as *malate* (and then converted back into *oxaloacetate* to transfer more *acetyl-CoA* out of the mitochondrion).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The cytosolic acetyl-CoA is used for fatty acid synthesis and the production of cholesterol.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Cholesterol can, in turn, be used to synthesize the steroid hormones, bile salts, and vitamin D.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The carbon skeletons of many non-essential amino acids are made from citric acid cycle intermediates.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] To turn them into amino acids the alpha keto-acids formed from the citric acid cycle intermediates have to acquire their amino groups from glutamate in a transamination reaction, in which pyridoxal phosphate is a cofactor.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In this reaction the glutamate is converted into *alpha-ketoglutarate*, which is a citric acid cycle intermediate.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The intermediates that can provide the carbon skeletons for amino acid synthesis are *oxaloacetate* which forms aspartate and asparagine; and *alpha-ketoglutarate* which forms glutamine, proline, and arginine.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Of these amino acids, aspartate and glutamine are used, together with carbon and nitrogen atoms from other sources, to form the purines that are used as the bases in DNA and RNA, as well as in ATP, AMP, GTP, NAD, FAD and CoA.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The pyrimidines are partly assembled from aspartate (derived from *oxaloacetate*).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The pyrimidines, thymine, cytosine and uracil, form the complementary bases to the purine bases in DNA and RNA, and are also components of CTP, UMP, UDP and UTP.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The majority of the carbon atoms in the porphyrins come from the citric acid cycle intermediate, *succinyl-CoA*.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] These molecules are an important component of the hemoproteins, such as hemoglobin, myoglobin and various cytochromes.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] During gluconeogenesis mitochondrial *oxaloacetate* is reduced to *malate* which is then transported out of the mitochondrion, to be oxidized back to oxaloacetate in the cytosol.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Cytosolic oxaloacetate is then decarboxylated to phosphoenolpyruvate by phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase, which is the rate limiting step in the conversion of nearly all the gluconeogenic precursors (such as the glucogenic amino acids and lactate) into glucose by the liver and kidney.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Because the citric acid cycle is involved in both catabolic and anabolic processes, it is known as an amphibolic pathway.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] The metabolic role of lactate is well recognized as a fuel for tissues, mitochondrial cytopathies such as DPH Cytopathy, and the scientific field of oncology (tumors).
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] In the classical Cori cycle, muscles produce lactate which is then taken up by the liver for gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] New studies suggest that lactate can be used as a source of carbon for the TCA cycle.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] It is believed that components of the citric acid cycle were derived from anaerobic bacteria, and that the TCA cycle itself may have evolved more than once.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] It may even predate biosis: the substrates appear to undergo most of the reactions spontaneously in the presence of persulfate radicals.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Alternatively, prebiotic synthesis of the citric acid cycle could have beginnings in the interstellar medium.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] Theoretically, several alternatives to the TCA cycle exist; however, the TCA cycle appears to be the most efficient.
[src:biochemistry/citric-acid-cycle] If several TCA alternatives had evolved independently, they all appear to have converged to the TCA cycle.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The wide occurrence of glycolysis in other species indicates that it is an ancient metabolic pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Indeed, the reactions that make up glycolysis and its parallel pathway, the pentose phosphate pathway, can occur in the oxygen-free conditions of the Archean oceans, also in the absence of enzymes, catalyzed by metal ions, meaning this is a plausible prebiotic pathway for abiogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The most common type of glycolysis is the *Embden–Meyerhof–Parnas (EMP) pathway*, which was discovered by Gustav Embden, Otto Meyerhof, and Jakub Karol Parnas.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Glycolysis also refers to other pathways, such as the *Entner–Doudoroff pathway* and various heterofermentative and homofermentative pathways.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] However, the discussion here will be limited to the Embden–Meyerhof–Parnas pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The use of symbols in this equation makes it appear unbalanced with respect to oxygen atoms, hydrogen atoms, and charges.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Charges are balanced by the difference between ADP and ATP.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In the cellular environment, all three hydroxyl groups of ADP dissociate into −O− and H+, giving ADP3−, and this ion tends to exist in an ionic bond with Mg2+, giving ADPMg−.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] ATP behaves identically except that it has four hydroxyl groups, giving ATPMg3−.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] When these differences along with the true charges on the two phosphate groups are considered together, the net charges of −4 on each side are balanced.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In high-oxygen (aerobic) conditions, eukaryotic cells can continue from glycolysis to metabolise the pyruvate through the citric acid cycle or the electron transport chain to produce significantly more ATP.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Importantly, under low-oxygen (anaerobic) conditions, glycolysis is the only biochemical pathway in eukaryotes that can generate ATP, and, for many anaerobic respiring organisms the most important producer of ATP.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Therefore, many organisms have evolved fermentation pathways to recycle NAD+ to continue glycolysis to produce ATP for survival.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] These pathways include ethanol fermentation and lactic acid fermentation.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The modern understanding of the pathway of glycolysis took almost 100 years to fully learn.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The combined results of many smaller experiments were required to understand the entire pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The first steps in understanding glycolysis began in the 19th century.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] For economic reasons, the French wine industry sought to investigate why wine sometimes turned distasteful, instead of fermenting into alcohol.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The French scientist Louis Pasteur researched this issue during the 1850s.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] His experiments showed that alcohol fermentation occurs by the action of living microorganisms, yeasts, and that glucose consumption decreased under aerobic conditions (the Pasteur effect).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The component steps of glycolysis were first analysed by the non-cellular fermentation experiments of Eduard Buchner during the 1890s.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Buchner demonstrated that the conversion of glucose to ethanol was possible using a non-living extract of yeast, due to the action of enzymes in the extract.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This experiment not only revolutionized biochemistry, but also allowed later scientists to analyze this pathway in a more controlled laboratory setting.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In a series of experiments (1905–1911), scientists Arthur Harden and William Young discovered more pieces of glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] They discovered the regulatory effects of ATP on glucose consumption during alcohol fermentation.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] They also shed light on the role of one compound as a glycolysis intermediate: fructose 1,6-bisphosphate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The elucidation of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate was accomplished by measuring CO2 levels when yeast juice was incubated with glucose.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] CO2 production increased rapidly then slowed down.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Harden and Young noted that this process would restart if an inorganic phosphate (Pi) was added to the mixture.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Harden and Young deduced that this process produced organic phosphate esters, and further experiments allowed them to extract fructose diphosphate (F-1,6-DP).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This experiment begun by observing that dialyzed (purified) yeast juice could not ferment or even create a sugar phosphate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This mixture was rescued with the addition of undialyzed yeast extract that had been boiled.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Boiling the yeast extract renders all proteins inactive (as it denatures them).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The ability of boiled extract plus dialyzed juice to complete fermentation suggests that the cofactors were non-protein in character.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In the 1920s Otto Meyerhof was able to link together some of the many individual pieces of glycolysis discovered by Buchner, Harden, and Young.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Meyerhof and his team were able to extract distinct glycolytic enzymes from muscle tissue, and combine them to artificially create the pathway from glycogen to lactic acid.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In one paper, Meyerhof and scientist Renate Junowicz-Kockolaty investigated the reaction that splits fructose 1,6-diphosphate into the two triose phosphates.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Previous work proposed that the split occurred via 1,3-diphosphoglyceraldehyde plus an oxidizing enzyme and cozymase.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Meyerhoff and Junowicz found that the equilibrium constant for the isomerase and aldoses reaction were not affected by inorganic phosphates or any other cozymase or oxidizing enzymes.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] They further removed diphosphoglyceraldehyde as a possible intermediate in glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] With all of these pieces available by the 1930s, Gustav Embden proposed a detailed, step-by-step outline of that pathway we now know as glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The biggest difficulties in determining the intricacies of the pathway were due to the very short lifetime and low steady-state concentrations of the intermediates of the fast glycolytic reactions.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] By the 1940s, Meyerhof, Embden and many other biochemists had finally completed the puzzle of glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The understanding of the isolated pathway has been expanded in the subsequent decades, to include further details of its regulation and integration with other metabolic pathways.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The first five steps of glycolysis are regarded as the preparatory (or investment) phase, since they consume energy to convert the glucose into two three-carbon sugar phosphates (G3P).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Once glucose enters the cell, the first step is phosphorylation of glucose by a family of enzymes called hexokinases to form glucose 6-phosphate (G6P).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This reaction consumes ATP, but it acts to keep the glucose concentration inside the cell low, promoting continuous transport of blood glucose into the cell through the plasma membrane transporters.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In addition, phosphorylation blocks the glucose from leaking out – the cell lacks transporters for G6P, and free diffusion out of the cell is prevented due to the charged nature of G6P.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Glucose may alternatively be formed from the phosphorolysis or hydrolysis of intracellular starch or glycogen.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In animals, an isozyme of hexokinase called glucokinase is also used in the liver, which has a much lower affinity for glucose (Km in the vicinity of normal glycemia), and differs in regulatory properties.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The various substrate affinities and regulation of this enzyme reflect the role of the liver in maintaining blood sugar levels.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] G6P is then rearranged into fructose 6-phosphate (F6P) by glucose phosphate isomerase.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Fructose can also enter the glycolytic pathway by phosphorylation at this point.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The change in structure is an isomerization, in which the G6P has been converted to F6P.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The reaction requires an enzyme, phosphoglucose isomerase, to proceed.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This reaction is freely reversible under normal cell conditions.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] However, it is often driven forward because of a low concentration of F6P, which is constantly consumed during the next step of glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Under conditions of high F6P concentration, this reaction readily runs in reverse.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This phenomenon can be explained through Le Chatelier's Principle.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Isomerization to a keto sugar is necessary for carbanion stabilization in the fourth reaction step (below).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The energy expenditure of another ATP in this step is justified in 2 ways: The glycolytic process (up to this step) becomes irreversible, and the energy supplied destabilizes the molecule.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Because the reaction catalyzed by phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK-1) is coupled to the hydrolysis of ATP (an energetically favorable step) it is, in essence, irreversible, and a distinct pathway must be used to do the reverse conversion during gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This makes the reaction a key regulatory point (see below).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Furthermore, the second phosphorylation event is necessary to allow the formation of two charged groups (rather than only one) in the subsequent step of glycolysis, ensuring the prevention of free diffusion of substrates out of the cell.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The same reaction can also be catalyzed by pyrophosphate-dependent phosphofructokinase (**PFP** or **PPi-PFK**), which is found in most plants, some bacteria, archea, and protists, but not in animals.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This enzyme uses pyrophosphate (PPi) as a phosphate donor instead of ATP.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] It is a reversible reaction, increasing the flexibility of glycolytic metabolism.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] A rarer ADP-dependent PFK enzyme variant has been identified in archaean species.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Destabilizing the molecule in the previous reaction allows the hexose ring to be split by aldolase into two triose sugars: dihydroxyacetone phosphate (a ketose), and glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (an aldose).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Two classes of aldolases exist: class I aldolases, present in animals and plants, and class II aldolases, present in fungi and bacteria.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The two classes use distinct mechanisms in cleaving the ketose ring.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Electrons delocalized in the carbon-carbon bond cleavage associate with the alcohol group.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The resulting carbanion is stabilized by resonance and by a positively charged prosthetic group.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Triosephosphate isomerase rapidly interconverts dihydroxyacetone phosphate with glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (**GADP**) that proceeds further into glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This is advantageous, as it directs dihydroxyacetone phosphate down the same pathway as glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate, simplifying regulation.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The second half of glycolysis is known as the pay-off phase, characterised by a net gain of the energy-rich molecules ATP and NADH.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Since glucose leads to two triose sugars in the preparatory phase, each reaction in the pay-off phase occurs twice per glucose molecule.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This yields 2 NADH molecules and 4 ATP molecules, leading to a net gain of 2 NADH molecules and 2 ATP molecules from the glycolytic pathway per glucose.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The aldehyde groups of the triose sugars are oxidised, and inorganic phosphate is added to them, forming 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The hydrogen is used to reduce two molecules of NAD+, a hydrogen carrier, to give NADH **+** H+ for each triose.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Hydrogen atom and ion balance and charge balance are both maintained because the phosphate (Pi) group actually exists in the form of a hydrogen phosphate anion (HPO2−4), which dissociates to contribute the extra H+ ion and gives a net charge of −3 on both sides.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Here, arsenate ([AsO4]3−), an anion akin to inorganic phosphate may replace phosphate as a substrate to form 1-arseno-3-phosphoglycerate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This, however, is unstable and readily hydrolyzes to form 3-phosphoglycerate, the intermediate in the next step of the pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] As a consequence of bypassing this step, the molecule of ATP generated from 1–3 bisphosphoglycerate in the next reaction will not be made, even though the reaction proceeds.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] As a result, arsenate is an uncoupler of glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This step is the enzymatic transfer of a phosphate group from 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate to ADP by phosphoglycerate kinase, forming ATP and 3-phosphoglycerate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] At this step, glycolysis has reached the break-even point: 2 molecules of ATP were consumed, and 2 new molecules have now been synthesized.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This step, one of the two substrate-level phosphorylation steps, requires ADP; thus, when the cell has plenty of ATP (and little ADP), this reaction does not occur.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Because ATP decays relatively quickly when it is not metabolized, this is an important regulatory point in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] ADP actually exists as ADPMg−, and ATP as ATPMg2−, balancing the charges at −5 both sides.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Phosphoglycerate mutase isomerises 3-phosphoglycerate into 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Enolase next converts 2-phosphoglycerate to phosphoenolpyruvate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This reaction is an elimination reaction involving an E1cB mechanism.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] A final substrate-level phosphorylation now forms a molecule of pyruvate and a molecule of ATP by means of the enzyme pyruvate kinase.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This serves as an additional regulatory step, similar to the phosphoglycerate kinase step.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The existence of more than one point of regulation indicates that intermediates between those points enter and leave the glycolysis pathway by other processes.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] For example, in the first regulated step, hexokinase converts glucose into glucose-6-phosphate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Instead of continuing through the glycolysis pathway, this intermediate can be converted into glucose storage molecules, such as glycogen or starch.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The reverse reaction, breaking down, e.g., glycogen, produces mainly glucose-6-phosphate; very little free glucose is formed in the reaction.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The glucose-6-phosphate so produced can enter glycolysis *after* the first control point.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In the second regulated step (the third step of glycolysis), phosphofructokinase converts fructose-6-phosphate into fructose-1,6-bisphosphate, which then is converted into glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The dihydroxyacetone phosphate can be removed from glycolysis by conversion into glycerol-3-phosphate, which can be used to form triglycerides.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Conversely, triglycerides can be broken down into fatty acids and glycerol; the latter, in turn, can be converted into dihydroxyacetone phosphate, which can enter glycolysis *after* the second control point.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The change in free energy, Δ*G*, for each step in the glycolysis pathway can be calculated using Δ*G* = Δ*G*°′ + *RT*ln *Q*, where *Q* is the reaction quotient.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This requires knowing the concentrations of the metabolites.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] All of these values are available for erythrocytes, with the exception of the concentrations of NAD+ and NADH.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The ratio of NAD+ to NADH in the cytoplasm is approximately 1000, which makes the oxidation of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (step 6) more favourable.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Using the measured concentrations of each step, and the standard free energy changes, the actual free energy change can be calculated.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] (Neglecting this is very common—the delta G of ATP hydrolysis in cells is not the standard free energy change of ATP hydrolysis quoted in textbooks).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] From measuring the physiological concentrations of metabolites in an erythrocyte it seems that about seven of the steps in glycolysis are in equilibrium for that cell type.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Three of the steps—the ones with large negative free energy changes—are not in equilibrium and are referred to as *irreversible*; such steps are often subject to regulation.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Step 5 in the figure is shown behind the other steps, because that step is a side-reaction that can decrease or increase the concentration of the intermediate glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] That compound is converted to dihydroxyacetone phosphate by the enzyme triose phosphate isomerase, which is a catalytically perfect enzyme; its rate is so fast that the reaction can be assumed to be in equilibrium.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The fact that Δ*G* is not zero indicates that the actual concentrations in the erythrocyte are not accurately known.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The enzymes that catalyse glycolysis are regulated via a range of biological mechanisms in order to control overall flux through the pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This is vital for both homeostasis in a static environment, and metabolic adaptation to a changing environment or need.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The details of regulation for some enzymes are highly conserved between species, whereas others vary widely.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Allosteric inhibition and activation by metabolites: In particular end-product inhibition of regulated enzymes by metabolites such as ATP serves as negative feedback regulation of the pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Allosteric inhibition and activation by Protein-protein interactions (PPI).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Indeed, some proteins interact with and regulate multiple glycolytic enzymes.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In particular, phosphorylation and dephosphorylation is a key mechanism of regulation of pyruvate kinase in the liver.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In animals, regulation of blood glucose levels by the pancreas in conjunction with the liver is a vital part of homeostasis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The beta cells in the pancreatic islets are sensitive to the blood glucose concentration.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] A rise in the blood glucose concentration causes them to release insulin into the blood, which has an effect particularly on the liver, but also on fat and muscle cells, causing these tissues to remove glucose from the blood.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] When the blood sugar falls the pancreatic beta cells cease insulin production, but, instead, stimulate the neighboring pancreatic alpha cells to release glucagon into the blood.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This, in turn, causes the liver to release glucose into the blood by breaking down stored glycogen, and by means of gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] If the fall in the blood glucose level is particularly rapid or severe, other glucose sensors cause the release of epinephrine from the adrenal glands into the blood.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This has the same action as glucagon on glucose metabolism, but its effect is more pronounced.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In the liver glucagon and epinephrine cause the phosphorylation of the key, regulated enzymes of glycolysis, fatty acid synthesis, cholesterol synthesis, gluconeogenesis, and glycogenolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Insulin has the opposite effect on these enzymes.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The phosphorylation and dephosphorylation of these enzymes (ultimately in response to the glucose level in the blood) is the dominant manner by which these pathways are controlled in the liver, fat, and muscle cells.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Thus the phosphorylation of phosphofructokinase inhibits glycolysis, whereas its dephosphorylation through the action of insulin stimulates glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The three regulatory enzymes are hexokinase (or glucokinase in the liver), phosphofructokinase, and pyruvate kinase.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The flux through the glycolytic pathway is adjusted in response to conditions both inside and outside the cell.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The internal factors that regulate glycolysis do so primarily to provide ATP in adequate quantities for the cell's needs.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The external factors act primarily on the liver, fat tissue, and muscles, which can remove large quantities of glucose from the blood after meals (thus preventing hyperglycemia by storing the excess glucose as fat or glycogen, depending on the tissue type).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The liver is also capable of releasing glucose into the blood between meals, during fasting, and exercise thus preventing hypoglycemia by means of glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] These latter reactions coincide with the halting of glycolysis in the liver.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In addition hexokinase and glucokinase act independently of the hormonal effects as controls at the entry points of glucose into the cells of distinct tissues.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Hexokinase responds to the glucose-6-phosphate (G6P) level in the cell, or, in the case of glucokinase, to the blood sugar level in the blood to impart entirely intracellular controls of the glycolytic pathway in distinct tissues (see below).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Excess citrate is exported from the mitochondrion back into the cytosol, where ATP citrate lyase regenerates acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate (OAA).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The acetyl-CoA is then used for fatty acid synthesis and cholesterol synthesis, two important ways of utilizing excess glucose when its concentration is high in blood.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The regulated enzymes catalyzing these reactions perform these functions when they have been dephosphorylated through the action of insulin on the liver cells.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Between meals, during fasting, exercise or hypoglycemia, glucagon and epinephrine are released into the blood.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This causes liver glycogen to be converted back to G6P, and then converted to glucose by the liver-specific enzyme glucose 6-phosphatase and released into the blood.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Glucagon and epinephrine also stimulate gluconeogenesis, which converts non-carbohydrate substrates into G6P, which joins the G6P derived from glycogen, or substitutes for it when the liver glycogen store have been depleted.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This is critical for brain function, since the brain utilizes glucose as an energy source under most conditions.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The simultaneously phosphorylation of, particularly, phosphofructokinase, but also, to a certain extent pyruvate kinase, prevents glycolysis occurring at the same time as gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] All cells contain the enzyme hexokinase, which catalyzes the conversion of glucose that has entered the cell into glucose-6-phosphate (G6P).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Since the cell membrane is impervious to G6P, hexokinase essentially acts to transport glucose into the cells from which it can then no longer escape.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Hexokinase is inhibited by high levels of G6P in the cell.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Thus the rate of entry of glucose into cells partially depends on how fast G6P can be disposed of by glycolysis, and by glycogen synthesis (in the cells which store glycogen, namely liver and muscles).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Glucokinase, unlike hexokinase, is not inhibited by G6P.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] It occurs in liver cells, and will only phosphorylate the glucose entering the cell to form G6P, when the glucose in the blood is abundant.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This being the first step in the glycolytic pathway in the liver, it therefore imparts an additional layer of control of the glycolytic pathway in this organ.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Phosphofructokinase is an important control point in the glycolytic pathway, since it is one of the irreversible steps and has key allosteric effectors, AMP and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate (F2,6BP).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] F2,6BP is a very potent activator of phosphofructokinase (PFK-1) that is synthesized when F6P is phosphorylated by a second phosphofructokinase (PFK2).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In the liver, when blood sugar is low and glucagon elevates cAMP, PFK2 is phosphorylated by protein kinase A.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The phosphorylation inactivates PFK2, and another domain on this protein becomes active as fructose bisphosphatase-2, which converts F2,6BP back to F6P.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Both glucagon and epinephrine cause high levels of cAMP in the liver.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The result of lower levels of liver F2,6BP is a decrease in activity of phosphofructokinase and an increase in activity of fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase, so that gluconeogenesis (in essence, "glycolysis in reverse") is favored.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This is consistent with the role of the liver in such situations, since the response of the liver to these hormones is to release glucose to the blood.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] ATP competes with AMP for the allosteric effector site on the PFK enzyme.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] ATP concentrations in cells are much higher than those of AMP, typically 100-fold higher, but the concentration of ATP does not change more than about 10% under physiological conditions, whereas a 10% drop in ATP results in a 6-fold increase in AMP.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Thus, the relevance of ATP as an allosteric effector is questionable.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] An increase in AMP is a consequence of a decrease in energy charge in the cell.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Citrate inhibits phosphofructokinase when tested *in vitro* by enhancing the inhibitory effect of ATP.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] However, it is doubtful that this is a meaningful effect *in vivo*, because citrate in the cytosol is utilized mainly for conversion to acetyl-CoA for fatty acid and cholesterol synthesis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] TIGAR, a p53 induced enzyme, is responsible for the regulation of phosphofructokinase and acts to protect against oxidative stress.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] TIGAR is a single enzyme with dual function that regulates F2,6BP.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] It can behave as a phosphatase (fructuose-2,6-bisphosphatase) which cleaves the phosphate at carbon-2 producing F6P.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] It can also behave as a kinase (PFK2) adding a phosphate onto carbon-2 of F6P which produces F2,6BP.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In humans, the TIGAR protein is encoded by *C12orf5* gene.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The TIGAR enzyme will hinder the forward progression of glycolysis, by creating a build up of fructose-6-phosphate (F6P) which is isomerized into glucose-6-phosphate (G6P).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The accumulation of G6P will shunt carbons into the pentose phosphate pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The final step of glycolysis is catalysed by pyruvate kinase to form pyruvate and another ATP.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] It is regulated by a range of transcriptional, covalent and non-covalent regulation mechanisms, which can vary widely.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] For example, in the liver, pyruvate kinase is regulated based on glucose availability.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] During fasting (no glucose available), glucagon activates protein kinase A which phosphorylates pyruvate kinase to inhibit it.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] An increase in blood sugar leads to secretion of insulin, which activates protein phosphatase 1, leading to dephosphorylation and re-activation of pyruvate kinase.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] These controls prevent pyruvate kinase from being active at the same time as the enzymes that catalyze the reverse reaction (pyruvate carboxylase and phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase), preventing a futile cycle.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Conversely, the isoform of pyruvate kinasein found in muscle is not affected by protein kinase A (which is activated by adrenaline in that tissue), so that glycolysis remains active in muscles even during fasting.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] If glycolysis were to continue indefinitely, all of the NAD+ would be used up, and glycolysis would stop.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] To allow glycolysis to continue, organisms must be able to oxidize NADH back to NAD+.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] How this is performed depends on which external electron acceptor is available.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This process occurs in the bacteria involved in making yogurt (the lactic acid causes the milk to curdle).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This process also occurs in animals under hypoxic (or partially anaerobic) conditions, found, for example, in overworked muscles that are starved of oxygen.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In many tissues, this is a cellular last resort for energy; most animal tissue cannot tolerate anaerobic conditions for an extended period of time.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Some organisms, such as yeast, convert NADH back to NAD+ in a process called ethanol fermentation.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In this process, the pyruvate is converted first to acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide, and then to ethanol.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Lactic acid fermentation and ethanol fermentation can occur in the absence of oxygen.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This anaerobic fermentation allows many single-cell organisms to use glycolysis as their only energy source.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Anoxic regeneration of NAD+ is only an effective means of energy production during short, intense exercise in vertebrates, for a period ranging from 10 seconds to 2 minutes during a maximal effort in humans.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] (At lower exercise intensities it can sustain muscle activity in diving animals, such as seals, whales and other aquatic vertebrates, for very much longer periods of time.) Under these conditions NAD+ is replenished by NADH donating its electrons to pyruvate to form lactate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This produces 2 ATP molecules per glucose molecule, or about 5% of glucose's energy potential (38 ATP molecules in bacteria).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] But the speed at which ATP is produced in this manner is about 100 times that of oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The pH in the cytoplasm quickly drops when hydrogen ions accumulate in the muscle, eventually inhibiting the enzymes involved in glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The burning sensation in muscles during hard exercise can be attributed to the release of hydrogen ions during the shift to glucose fermentation from glucose oxidation to carbon dioxide and water, when aerobic metabolism can no longer keep pace with the energy demands of the muscles.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] These hydrogen ions form a part of lactic acid.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The body falls back on this less efficient but faster method of producing ATP under low oxygen conditions.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The liver in mammals gets rid of this excess lactate by transforming it back into pyruvate under aerobic conditions; see Cori cycle.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Fermentation of pyruvate to lactate is sometimes also called "anaerobic glycolysis", however, glycolysis ends with the production of pyruvate regardless of the presence or absence of oxygen.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In the above two examples of fermentation, NADH is oxidized by transferring two electrons to pyruvate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In aerobic eukaryotes, a complex mechanism has developed to use the oxygen in air as the final electron acceptor, in a process called oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Aerobic prokaryotes, which lack mitochondria, use a variety of simpler mechanisms.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The pyruvate produced by glycolysis is an important intermediary in the conversion of carbohydrates into fatty acids and cholesterol.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This occurs via the conversion of pyruvate into acetyl-CoA in the mitochondrion.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] However, this acetyl CoA needs to be transported into cytosol where the synthesis of fatty acids and cholesterol occurs.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] To obtain cytosolic acetyl-CoA, citrate (produced by the condensation of acetyl CoA with oxaloacetate) is removed from the citric acid cycle and carried across the inner mitochondrial membrane into the cytosol.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The oxaloacetate is returned to mitochondrion as malate (and then back into oxaloacetate to transfer more acetyl-CoA out of the mitochondrion).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Cholesterol can be used as is, as a structural component of cellular membranes, or it can be used to synthesize the steroid hormones, bile salts, and vitamin D.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] In the citric acid cycle all the intermediates (e.g. citrate, iso-citrate, alpha-ketoglutarate, succinate, fumarate, malate and oxaloacetate) are regenerated during each turn of the cycle.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] To cataplerotically remove oxaloacetate from the citric cycle, malate can be transported from the mitochondrion into the cytoplasm, decreasing the amount of oxaloacetate that can be regenerated.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Furthermore, citric acid intermediates are constantly used to form a variety of substances such as the purines, pyrimidines and porphyrins.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] A number of anaerobic eukaryotes have acquired the ability to perform *extended hydrolysis*.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The prototypical example is the hydrogenosome, but there are also transitional H2-producing mitochondria with this function.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The net reaction is conversion of singular equivalents of pyruvate, ADP, and Pi into ATP, CO2, acetate, and H2.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This article concentrates on the catabolic role of glycolysis with regard to converting potential chemical energy to usable chemical energy during the oxidation of glucose to pyruvate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Many of the metabolites in the glycolytic pathway are also used by anabolic pathways, and, as a consequence, flux through the pathway is critical to maintain a supply of carbon skeletons for biosynthesis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The following metabolic pathways are all strongly reliant on glycolysis as a source of metabolites: and many more.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Although gluconeogenesis and glycolysis share many intermediates the one is not functionally a branch or tributary of the other.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] There are two regulatory steps in both pathways which, when active in the one pathway, are automatically inactive in the other.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The two processes can therefore not be simultaneously active.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] Indeed, if both sets of reactions were highly active at the same time the net result would be the hydrolysis of four high energy phosphate bonds (two ATP and two GTP) per reaction cycle.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] NAD+ is the oxidizing agent in glycolysis, as it is in most other energy yielding metabolic reactions (e.g. beta-oxidation of fatty acids, and during the citric acid cycle).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] The NADH thus produced is primarily used to ultimately transfer electrons to O2 to produce water, or, when O2 is not available, to produce compounds such as lactate or ethanol (see *Anoxic regeneration of NAD+* above).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] NADH is rarely used for synthetic processes, the notable exception being gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] During fatty acid and cholesterol synthesis the reducing agent is NADPH.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] This difference exemplifies a general principle that NADPH is consumed during biosynthetic reactions, whereas NADH is generated in energy-yielding reactions.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] When malate is oxidatively decarboxylated by "NADP+-linked malic enzyme" pyruvate, CO2 and NADPH are formed.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p01] NADPH is also formed by the pentose phosphate pathway which converts glucose into ribose, which can be used in synthesis of nucleotides and nucleic acids, or it can be catabolized to pyruvate.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Cellular uptake of glucose occurs in response to insulin signals, and glucose is subsequently broken down through glycolysis, lowering blood sugar levels.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] However, insulin resistance or low insulin levels seen in diabetes result in hyperglycemia, where glucose levels in the blood rise and glucose is not properly taken up by cells.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Hepatocytes further contribute to this hyperglycemia through gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Glycolysis in hepatocytes controls hepatic glucose production, and when glucose is overproduced by the liver without having a means of being broken down by the body, hyperglycemia results.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Glycolytic mutations are generally rare due to importance of the metabolic pathway; the majority of occurring mutations result in an inability of the cell to respire, and therefore cause the death of the cell at an early stage.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] However, some mutations (glycogen storage diseases and other inborn errors of carbohydrate metabolism) are seen with one notable example being pyruvate kinase deficiency, leading to chronic hemolytic anemia.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] In combined malonic and methylmalonic aciduria (CMAMMA) due to ACSF3 deficiency, glycolysis is reduced by −50%, which is caused by reduced lipoylation of mitochondrial enzymes such as the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex and α-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase complex.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Malignant tumor cells perform glycolysis at a rate that is ten times faster than their noncancerous tissue counterparts.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] During their genesis, limited capillary support often results in hypoxia (decreased O2 supply) within the tumor cells.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Thus, these cells rely on anaerobic metabolic processes such as glycolysis for ATP (adenosine triphosphate).
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Some tumor cells overexpress specific glycolytic enzymes which result in higher rates of glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Often these enzymes are Isoenzymes, of traditional glycolysis enzymes, that vary in their susceptibility to traditional feedback inhibition.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] The increase in glycolytic activity ultimately counteracts the effects of hypoxia by generating sufficient ATP from this anaerobic pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] This phenomenon was first described in 1930 by Otto Warburg and is referred to as the Warburg effect.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] The Warburg hypothesis claims that cancer is primarily caused by dysfunctionality in mitochondrial metabolism, rather than because of the uncontrolled growth of cells.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] A number of theories have been advanced to explain the Warburg effect.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] One such theory suggests that the increased glycolysis is a normal protective process of the body and that malignant change could be primarily caused by energy metabolism.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] There is ongoing research to affect mitochondrial metabolism and treat cancer by reducing glycolysis and thus starving cancerous cells in various new ways, including a ketogenic diet.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] The diagram below shows human protein names.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Names in other organisms may differ, and the numbers of isozymes (such as HK1, HK2, ...) likely differ also.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Some of the metabolites in glycolysis have alternative names and nomenclature.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] In part, this is because some of them are common to other pathways, such as the Calvin cycle.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] The intermediates of glycolysis depicted in Fischer projections show the chemical changing step by step.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Such image can be compared to polygonal model representation.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Glycolysis - Structure of anaerobic glycolysis components showed using Fischer projections, left, and polygonal model, right.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] The phosphorylation reactions from ATP, as well the ADP phosphorylation reactions in later steps of glycolysis are shown as ~P respectively entering or going out the pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] or NADH are observed as hydrogens "2H" going out or entering the pathway.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] The intermediates of glycolysis depicted in skeletal diagram show the chemical structures changing step by step, with cofactors such as NADH, ATP, and water and phosphates to balance reactions' stoichiometry.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Each enzyme that mediates each reaction is indicated in the reversible arrow model of chemical reactions, as most enzymes catalyze bidirectional chemical reactions.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Duplicates, such as the reversible re-arrangement between dihydroxyacetone and glyceraldehyde on the bottom row of reactions, represent two moles of C3 fragments derived from a single mole of the preceding C6 fragment of fructose bisphosphate, giving a net of two ATP generated.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Thus the diagram must be read with rules of stoichiometry and balance-of-matter principles in mind.
[src:biochemistry/glycolysis-p02] Follow the green "START" button to the red "END" button to trace the pathway through the structural pathway diagram.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Metabolic reactions may be categorized as *catabolic*—the *breaking down* of compounds (for example, of glucose to pyruvate by cellular respiration); or *anabolic*—the *building up* (biosynthesis) of compounds (such as proteins, carbohydrates, lipids, and nucleic acids).
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Usually, catabolism releases energy, and anabolism consumes energy.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The chemical reactions of metabolism are organized into metabolic pathways, in which one chemical is transformed through a series of steps into another chemical, each step being facilitated by a specific enzyme.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Enzymes are crucial to metabolism because they allow organisms to drive reactions that require energy and will not occur by themselves, by coupling them to spontaneous reactions that release energy.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Enzymes act as catalysts—they allow a reaction to proceed more rapidly—and they also allow the regulation of the rate of a metabolic reaction, for example, in response to changes in the cell's environment or to signals from other cells.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The metabolic system of a particular organism determines which substances it will find nutritious and which poisonous.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] For example, some prokaryotes use hydrogen sulfide (H₂S) as a nutrient, yet this gas is poisonous to some animals.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Since hydrogen sulfide is a gasotransmitter, certain mammals including humans produce H₂S naturally in very small concentrations where it serves vital signaling and regulatory functions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The basal metabolic rate of an organism is the measure of the amount of energy consumed by all of these chemical reactions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] A notable feature of metabolism is the similarity of the basic metabolic pathways among vastly different species.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] For example, the set of carboxylic acids that are best known as the intermediates in the citric acid cycle are present in all known organisms, being found in species as diverse as the unicellular bacterium *Escherichia coli* (*E. coli)* and huge multicellular organisms like elephants.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These similarities in metabolic pathways are likely due to their early appearance in evolutionary history, and their retention is likely due to their efficacy.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In various diseases, such as type II diabetes, metabolic syndrome, and cancer, normal metabolism is disrupted.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The metabolism of cancer cells is also different from the metabolism of normal cells, and these differences can be used to find targets for therapeutic intervention in cancer.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Most of the structures that make up animals, plants and microbes are made from four basic classes of molecules: amino acids, carbohydrates, nucleic acid and lipids (often called fats).
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] As these molecules are vital for life, metabolic reactions either focus on making these molecules during the construction of cells and tissues, or on breaking them down and using them to obtain energy, by their digestion.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These biochemicals can be joined to make polymers such as DNA and proteins, essential macromolecules of life.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Proteins are made of amino acids arranged in a linear chain joined by peptide bonds.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Many proteins are enzymes that catalyze the chemical reactions in metabolism.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Other proteins have structural or mechanical functions, such as those that form the cytoskeleton, a system of scaffolding that maintains the cell's shape.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Proteins are also important in cell signaling, immune responses, cell adhesion, active transport across membranes, and the cell cycle.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Amino acids also contribute to cellular energy metabolism by providing a carbon source for entry into the citric acid cycle (tricarboxylic acid cycle), especially when a primary source of energy, such as glucose, is scarce, or when cells undergo metabolic stress.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Lipids are the most diverse group of biochemicals.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Their main structural uses are as part of internal and external biological membranes such as the cell membrane.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Lipids contain a long, non-polar hydrocarbon chain with a small polar region containing oxygen.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Lipids are usually defined as hydrophobic or amphipathic biological molecules but will dissolve in organic solvents such as ethanol, benzene or chloroform.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The fats are a large group of compounds that contain fatty acids and glycerol; a glycerol molecule attached to three fatty acids by ester linkages is called a triacylglyceride.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Several variations of the basic structure exist, including backbones such as sphingosine in sphingomyelin, and hydrophilic groups such as phosphate in phospholipids.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Steroids such as sterol are another major class of lipids.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Carbohydrates are aldehydes or ketones, with many hydroxyl groups attached, that can exist as straight chains or rings.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Carbohydrates are the most abundant biological molecules, and fill numerous roles, such as the storage and transport of energy (starch, glycogen) and structural components (cellulose in plants, chitin in animals).
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The basic carbohydrate units are called monosaccharides and include galactose, fructose, and most importantly glucose.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Monosaccharides can be linked together to form polysaccharides in almost limitless ways.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The two nucleic acids, DNA and RNA, are polymers of nucleotides.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Each nucleotide is composed of a phosphate attached to a ribose or deoxyribose sugar group which is attached to a nitrogenous base.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Nucleic acids are critical for the storage and use of genetic information, and their interpretation through the processes of transcription and protein biosynthesis.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This information is protected by DNA repair mechanisms and propagated through DNA replication.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Many viruses have an RNA genome, such as HIV, which uses reverse transcription to create a DNA template from its viral RNA genome.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] RNA in ribozymes such as spliceosomes and ribosomes is similar to enzymes as it can catalyze chemical reactions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Individual nucleosides are made by attaching a nucleobase to a ribose sugar.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These bases are heterocyclic rings containing nitrogen, classified as purines or pyrimidines.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Nucleotides also act as coenzymes in metabolic-group-transfer reactions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Metabolism involves a vast array of chemical reactions, but most fall under a few basic types of reactions that involve the transfer of functional groups of atoms and their bonds within molecules.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This common chemistry allows cells to use a small set of metabolic intermediates to carry chemical groups between different reactions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These group-transfer intermediates are called coenzymes.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Each class of group-transfer reactions is carried out by a particular coenzyme, which is the substrate for a set of enzymes that produce it, and a set of enzymes that consume it.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These coenzymes are therefore continuously made, consumed and then recycled.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] One central coenzyme is adenosine triphosphate (ATP) which is the energy currency of cells.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This nucleotide is used to transfer chemical energy between different chemical reactions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] There is only a small amount of ATP in cells, but as it is continuously regenerated, the human body can use about its own weight in ATP per day.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] ATP acts as a bridge between catabolism and anabolism.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Catabolism breaks down molecules, and anabolism puts them together.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Catabolic reactions generate ATP, and anabolic reactions consume it.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] It also serves as a carrier of phosphate groups in phosphorylation reactions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] A vitamin is an organic compound needed in small quantities that cannot be made in cells.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In human nutrition, most vitamins function as coenzymes after modification; for example, all water-soluble vitamins are phosphorylated or are coupled to nucleotides when they are used in cells.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+), a derivative of vitamin B3 (niacin), is an important coenzyme that acts as a hydrogen acceptor.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Hundreds of separate types of dehydrogenases remove electrons from their substrates and reduce NAD+ into NADH.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This reduced form of the coenzyme is then a substrate for any of the reductases in the cell that need to transfer hydrogen atoms to their substrates.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide exists in two related forms in the cell, NADH and NADPH.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The NAD+/NADH form is more important in catabolic reactions, while NADP+/NADPH is used in anabolic reactions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Inorganic elements play critical roles in metabolism; some are abundant (e.g. sodium and potassium) while others function at minute concentrations.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] About 99% of a human's body weight is made up of the elements carbon, nitrogen, calcium, sodium, chlorine, potassium, hydrogen, phosphorus, oxygen and sulfur.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Organic compounds (proteins, lipids and carbohydrates) contain the majority of the carbon and nitrogen; most of the oxygen and hydrogen is present as water.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The abundant inorganic elements act as electrolytes.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The most important ions are sodium, potassium, calcium, magnesium, chloride, phosphate and the organic ion bicarbonate.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The maintenance of precise ion gradients across cell membranes maintains osmotic pressure and pH.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Ions are also critical for nerve and muscle function, as action potentials in these tissues are produced by the exchange of electrolytes between the extracellular fluid and the cell's fluid, the cytosol.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Electrolytes enter and leave cells through proteins in the cell membrane called ion channels.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] For example, muscle contraction depends upon the movement of calcium, sodium and potassium through ion channels in the cell membrane and T-tubules.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Transition metals are usually present as trace elements in organisms, with zinc and iron being most abundant of those.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Metal cofactors are bound tightly to specific sites in proteins; although enzyme cofactors can be modified during catalysis, they always return to their original state by the end of the reaction catalyzed.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Metal micronutrients are taken up into organisms by specific transporters and bind to storage proteins such as ferritin or metallothionein when not in use.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Catabolism is the set of metabolic processes that break down large molecules.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These include breaking down and oxidizing food molecules.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The purpose of the catabolic reactions is to provide the energy and components needed by anabolic reactions which build molecules.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The exact nature of these catabolic reactions differ from organism to organism, and organisms can be classified based on their sources of energy, hydrogen, and carbon (their primary nutritional groups), as shown in the table below.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Organic molecules are used as a source of hydrogen atoms or electrons by organotrophs, while lithotrophs use inorganic substrates.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Whereas phototrophs convert sunlight to chemical energy, chemotrophs depend on redox reactions that involve the transfer of electrons from reduced donor molecules such as organic molecules, hydrogen, hydrogen sulfide or ferrous ions to oxygen, nitrate or sulfate.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In animals, these reactions involve complex organic molecules that are broken down to simpler molecules, such as carbon dioxide and water.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Photosynthetic organisms, such as plants and cyanobacteria, use similar electron-transfer reactions to store energy absorbed from sunlight.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The most common set of catabolic reactions in animals can be separated into three main stages.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In the first stage, large organic molecules, such as proteins, polysaccharides or lipids, are digested into their smaller components outside cells.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Next, these smaller molecules are taken up by cells and converted to smaller molecules, usually acetyl coenzyme A (acetyl-CoA), which releases some energy.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Finally, the acetyl group on acetyl-CoA is oxidized to water and carbon dioxide during the citric acid cycle and electron transport chain, releasing more energy while reducing the coenzyme nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) into NADH.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Macromolecules cannot be directly processed by cells.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Macromolecules must be broken into smaller units before they can be used in cell metabolism.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Different classes of enzymes are used to digest these polymers.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These digestive enzymes include proteases that digest proteins into amino acids, as well as glycoside hydrolases that digest polysaccharides into simple sugars known as monosaccharides.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Microbes simply secrete digestive enzymes into their surroundings, while animals only secrete these enzymes from specialized cells in their guts, including the stomach, pancreas, and in salivary glands.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The amino acids or sugars released by these extracellular enzymes are then pumped into cells by active transport proteins.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Carbohydrate catabolism is the breakdown of carbohydrates into smaller units.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Carbohydrates are usually taken into cells after they have been digested into monosaccharides such as glucose and fructose.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Once inside, the major route of breakdown is glycolysis, in which glucose is converted into pyruvate.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This process generates the energy-conveying molecule NADH from NAD+, and generates ATP from ADP for use in powering many processes within the cell.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Pyruvate is an intermediate in several metabolic pathways, but the majority is converted to acetyl-CoA and fed into the citric acid cycle, which enables more ATP production by means of oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This oxidation consumes molecular oxygen and releases water and the waste product carbon dioxide.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The lactate is later converted back to pyruvate for ATP production where energy is needed, or back to glucose in the Cori cycle.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] An alternative route for glucose breakdown is the pentose phosphate pathway, which produces less energy but supports anabolism (biomolecule synthesis).
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This pathway reduces the coenzyme NADP+ to NADPH and produces pentose compounds such as ribose 5-phosphate for synthesis of many biomolecules such as nucleotides and aromatic amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Fats are catabolized by hydrolysis to free fatty acids and glycerol.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The glycerol enters glycolysis and the fatty acids are broken down by beta oxidation to release acetyl-CoA, which then is fed into the citric acid cycle.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Fatty acids release more energy upon oxidation than carbohydrates.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Steroids are also broken down by some bacteria in a process similar to beta oxidation, and this breakdown process involves the release of significant amounts of acetyl-CoA, propionyl-CoA, and pyruvate, which can all be used by the cell for energy.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] *M. tuberculosis* can also grow on the lipid cholesterol as a sole source of carbon, and genes involved in the cholesterol-use pathway(s) have been validated as important during various stages of the infection lifecycle of *M. tuberculosis*.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Amino acids are either used to synthesize proteins and other biomolecules, or oxidized to urea and carbon dioxide to produce energy.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The amino group is fed into the urea cycle, leaving a deaminated carbon skeleton in the form of a keto acid.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Several of these keto acids are intermediates in the citric acid cycle, for example α-ketoglutarate formed by deamination of glutamate.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In oxidative phosphorylation, the electrons removed from organic molecules in areas such as the citric acid cycle are transferred to oxygen and the energy released is used to make ATP.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This is done in eukaryotes by a series of proteins in the membranes of mitochondria called the electron transport chain.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In prokaryotes, these proteins are found in the cell's inner membrane.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These proteins use the energy from reduced molecules like NADH to pump protons across a membrane.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Pumping protons out of the mitochondria creates a proton concentration difference across the membrane and generates an electrochemical gradient.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This force drives protons back into the mitochondrion through the base of an enzyme called ATP synthase.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The flow of protons makes the stalk subunit rotate, causing the active site of the synthase domain to change shape and phosphorylate adenosine diphosphate—turning it into ATP.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Chemolithotrophy is a type of metabolism found in prokaryotes where energy is obtained from the oxidation of inorganic compounds.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These organisms can use hydrogen, reduced sulfur compounds (such as sulfide, hydrogen sulfide and thiosulfate), ferrous iron (Fe(II)) or ammonia as sources of reducing power and they gain energy from the oxidation of these compounds.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These microbial processes are important in global biogeochemical cycles such as acetogenesis, nitrification and denitrification and are critical for soil fertility.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The energy in sunlight is captured by plants, cyanobacteria, purple bacteria, green sulfur bacteria and some protists.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This process is often coupled to the conversion of carbon dioxide into organic compounds, as part of photosynthesis, which is discussed below.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The energy capture and carbon fixation systems can, however, operate separately in prokaryotes, as purple bacteria and green sulfur bacteria can use sunlight as a source of energy, while switching between carbon fixation and the fermentation of organic compounds.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In many organisms, the capture of solar energy is similar in principle to oxidative phosphorylation, as it involves the storage of energy as a proton concentration gradient.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This proton motive force then drives ATP synthesis.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The electrons needed to drive this electron transport chain come from light-gathering proteins called photosynthetic reaction centres.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Reaction centers are classified into two types depending on the nature of photosynthetic pigment present, with most photosynthetic bacteria only having one type, while plants and cyanobacteria have two.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In plants, algae, and cyanobacteria, photosystem II uses light energy to remove electrons from water, releasing oxygen as a waste product.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The electrons then flow to the cytochrome b6f complex, which uses their energy to pump protons across the thylakoid membrane in the chloroplast.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These protons move back through the membrane as they drive the ATP synthase, as before.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The electrons then flow through photosystem I and can then be used to reduce the coenzyme NADP+.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This coenzyme can enter the Calvin cycle or be recycled for further ATP generation.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Anabolism in organisms can be different according to the source of constructed molecules in their cells.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Autotrophs such as plants can construct the complex organic molecules in their cells such as polysaccharides and proteins from simple molecules like carbon dioxide and water.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Heterotrophs, on the other hand, require a source of more complex substances, such as monosaccharides and amino acids, to produce these complex molecules.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Organisms can be further classified by ultimate source of their energy: photoautotrophs and photoheterotrophs obtain energy from light, whereas chemoautotrophs and chemoheterotrophs obtain energy from oxidation reactions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Photosynthesis is the synthesis of carbohydrates from sunlight and carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In plants, cyanobacteria and algae, oxygenic photosynthesis splits water, with oxygen produced as a waste product.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This process uses the ATP and NADPH produced by the photosynthetic reaction centres, as described above, to convert CO2 into glycerate 3-phosphate, which can then be converted into glucose.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This carbon-fixation reaction is carried out by the enzyme RuBisCO as part of the Calvin–Benson cycle.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Three types of photosynthesis occur in plants, C3 carbon fixation, C4 carbon fixation and CAM photosynthesis.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These differ by the route that carbon dioxide takes to the Calvin cycle, with C3 plants fixing CO2 directly, while C4 and CAM photosynthesis incorporate the CO2 into other compounds first, as adaptations to deal with intense sunlight and dry conditions.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In photosynthetic prokaryotes the mechanisms of carbon fixation are more diverse.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Here, carbon dioxide can be fixed by the Calvin–Benson cycle, a reversed citric acid cycle, or the carboxylation of acetyl-CoA.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Prokaryotic chemoautotrophs also fix CO2 through the Calvin–Benson cycle, but use energy from inorganic compounds to drive the reaction.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In carbohydrate anabolism, simple organic acids can be converted into monosaccharides such as glucose and then used to assemble polysaccharides such as starch.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The generation of glucose from compounds like pyruvate, lactate, glycerol, glycerate 3-phosphate and amino acids is called gluconeogenesis.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Gluconeogenesis converts pyruvate to glucose-6-phosphate through a series of intermediates, many of which are shared with glycolysis.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] However, this pathway is not simply glycolysis run in reverse, as several steps are catalyzed by non-glycolytic enzymes.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] This is important as it allows the formation and breakdown of glucose to be regulated separately, and prevents both pathways from running simultaneously in a futile cycle.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Although fat is a common way of storing energy, in vertebrates such as humans the fatty acids in these stores cannot be converted to glucose through gluconeogenesis as these organisms cannot convert acetyl-CoA into pyruvate; plants do, but animals do not, have the necessary enzymatic machinery.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] As a result, after long-term starvation, vertebrates need to produce ketone bodies from fatty acids to replace glucose in tissues such as the brain that cannot metabolize fatty acids.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In other organisms such as plants and bacteria, this metabolic problem is solved using the glyoxylate cycle, which bypasses the decarboxylation step in the citric acid cycle and allows the transformation of acetyl-CoA to oxaloacetate, where it can be used for the production of glucose.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Other than fat, glucose is stored in most tissues, as an energy resource available within the tissue through glycogenesis which was usually being used to maintained glucose level in blood.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Polysaccharides and glycans are made by the sequential addition of monosaccharides by glycosyltransferase from a reactive sugar-phosphate donor such as uridine diphosphate glucose (UDP-Glc) to an acceptor hydroxyl group on the growing polysaccharide.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] As any of the hydroxyl groups on the ring of the substrate can be acceptors, the polysaccharides produced can have straight or branched structures.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The polysaccharides produced can have structural or metabolic functions themselves, or be transferred to lipids and proteins by the enzymes oligosaccharyltransferases.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Fatty acids are made by fatty acid synthases that polymerize and then reduce acetyl-CoA units.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The acyl chains in the fatty acids are extended by a cycle of reactions that add the acyl group, reduce it to an alcohol, dehydrate it to an alkene group and then reduce it again to an alkane group.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] The enzymes of fatty acid biosynthesis are divided into two groups: in animals and fungi, all these fatty acid synthase reactions are carried out by a single multifunctional type I protein, while in plant plastids and bacteria separate type II enzymes perform each step in the pathway.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Terpenes and isoprenoids are a large class of lipids that include the carotenoids and form the largest class of plant natural products.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These compounds are made by the assembly and modification of isoprene units donated from the reactive precursors isopentenyl pyrophosphate and dimethylallyl pyrophosphate.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] These precursors can be made in different ways.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] In animals and archaea, the mevalonate pathway produces these compounds from acetyl-CoA, while in plants and bacteria the non-mevalonate pathway uses pyruvate and glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate as substrates.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] One important reaction that uses these activated isoprene donors is sterol biosynthesis.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Here, the isoprene units are joined to make squalene and then folded up and formed into a set of rings to make lanosterol.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Lanosterol can then be converted into other sterols such as cholesterol and ergosterol.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Organisms vary in their ability to synthesize the 20 common amino acids.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Most bacteria and plants can synthesize all twenty, but mammals can only synthesize eleven nonessential amino acids, so nine essential amino acids must be obtained from food.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Some simple parasites, such as the bacteria *Mycoplasma pneumoniae*, lack all amino acid synthesis and take their amino acids directly from their hosts.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] All amino acids are synthesized from intermediates in glycolysis, the citric acid cycle, or the pentose phosphate pathway.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Nitrogen is provided by glutamate and glutamine.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Nonessential amino acid synthesis depends on the formation of the appropriate alpha-keto acid, which is then transaminated to form an amino acid.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Amino acids are made into proteins by being joined in a chain of peptide bonds.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Each different protein has a unique sequence of amino acid residues: this is its primary structure.
[src:biochemistry/metabolism] Just as the letters of the alphabet can be combined to form an almost endless variety of words, amino acids can be linked in varying sequences to form a huge variety of proteins.
